<HEAD>Bermuda Prepares For Hurricane Gabrielle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The hurricane's ..., to UPDATE wind force; SUBS
grafs 9-12, `At 6 p.m. ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT
positions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical storm-force winds swept the island of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> on Thursday, forcing boats to stay in port as a weakened Hurricane <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> approached. Hurricane Felix, meanwhile, dwindled into a tropical storm. <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> was heading due north, with its center passing about 300 miles east of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> late Thursday, forecasters said. The hurricane's winds weakened earlier in the day from 135 mph to 105 mph, but then rose by 10:30 p.m. EDT to 110 mph. Little change in strength was expected for <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> as it headed towards Tropical Storm Felix. `` The winds wo n't change much until it reaches cooler waters,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, director of the National Hurricane Center. Swells in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>'s harbors were reported at 10 feet, and the island's eastern tip reported swells of 15 to 20 feet. The high seas, combined with winds of 30 to 35 mph, prevented any seagoing traffic around the island. Otherwise, <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>'s residents were making few preparations for the storm, Sheets said. Strong winds stretched as far as 1,000 miles from <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON>'s center, reaching the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> `` A ship 60 miles off the coast of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> reported seeing 12 - to 15-foot seas,'' Sheets said High seas were also reported off the coast of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. At 10:30 p.m. EDT Thursday, Hurricane <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> was centered near 32.6 degrees north latitude and 59.6 degrees west longitude, or 310 miles east of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. It was traveling north at nearly 17 mph. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> was downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical storm earlier Thursday as it continued to weaken. The tropical storm posed no threat to land on its northward trek. Forecasters expect <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> to turn toward the northwest and become engulfed in the larger <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> system. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> is traveling northward at 7 mph with winds of 60 mph. At 10:30 p.m. EDT Thursday, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> was located near 41.0 degrees north latitude and 48.5 degrees west longitude, or about 450 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Race </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> was the sixth and <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> the seventh named storms of the 1989 Atlantic hurricane season. Storms are named when their winds reach 39 mph, and are classified as hurricanes when they grow to 74 mph.
</TEXT>
