<HEAD>Strike Accord Seen as Blow to Union Corruption in Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assembly plants, back in operation after winning a three-week labor dispute, have blazed the trail for other companies to fight the extraordinary power labor unions hold in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, industry spokesmen say. A union power struggle that shut down 15 American plants known as maquiladoras in the border city of <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION> ended with labor and government officials agreeing Aug. 18 to let the workers form a union independent of the nationally powerful <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> whose local representative forced the workers to strike. `` It definitely means that companies can take a stand against illegal activities and corruption and be successsul,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, manager for <ORGANIZATION> Reynosa </ORGANIZATION>'s West Bend plant. `` We blazed a new trail.'' The strike was settled after intervention of President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s government in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has made clear he will not let unions stand in the way of his goal of modernizing the Mexican economy and attracting more foreign investors. `` The <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> government has acted in a certain direction to remove as much of the corruption as it possibly can,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Kezsbom </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> whose <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION> plant was closed in the strike. `` He does n't want to have the negative publicity that occurred out of this permeate throughout the world. The issue was the expansion of the maquiladora industry in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' Maquiladoras, in which foreign-owned companies take advantage of cheap Mexican labor to produce goods for sale in their own countries or elsewhere, have become a top foreign income earner for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The industry, which generated $ 2.3 billion in foreign currency last year, has grown by more than 70 percent since 1985 and employs about 392,000 people, mainly along the U.S.-Mexican border. The strike cost an estimated $ 500,000 a day in lost production, but plant managers said it was worth it because the outcome was favorable to them. Although the plant workers indicated no great sympathy for a walkout, they went on strike July 25 on the orders of <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, a local leader of the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>. Strike flags were hoisted. Traditionally in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, workers who violate strike flags face severe consequences, including possible physical harm, immediately or later. The plants, nevertheless, continued to pay the workers their wages and benefits, averaging about $ 1.20 a hour, during the strike. <PERSON> Kezsbom </PERSON> said the American managers resisted <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, who controls most of the labor contracts at <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>'s 27 other maquiladoras, because they considered him corrupt. <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> forced companies to give him control of trucking contracts, waste disposal and scrap resale, and to issue food coupons good only at stores he controls. The coupons are part of the employee benefit packages. The nearly 2,000 workers at the plants <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> shut down waited for two weeks while plant managers and business leaders pleaded with the federal government in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to step in. Then, frustrated by government inaction, about 900 workers ripped down the strike flags, stormed back into their plants and went to work. That same day <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> met with industry leaders in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and promised the government would intervene. Gov. <PERSON> Americo </PERSON> <PERSON> Villarreal </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tamaulipas </LOCATION> summoned the managers to a meeting in the state capital, <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>, the next day to work out an accord giving the plant workers the right to form an independent union. The agreement surprised those familiar with the strength of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest labor organization and a powerful sector of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Although the agreement stipulates that only workers from the affected 15 plants can join the independent union, industry spokesmen say it may open a new era of labor relations in <LOCATION> Tamaulipas </LOCATION> and other Mexican states with maquiladora plants.
