<FIRST>r e BC-Kabuki     09-07 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kabuki,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kabuki Troupe Opens in Met Opera House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans who only occasionally see Japanese kabuki theater may not find <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>'s Kabuki as controversial as publicity before its appearances here and in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has led them to expect. Except for some acrobatics, quick costume changes and one exit on wires through the sky, at Wednesday's first of eight performances at the Metropolitan Opera, <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>'s Kabuki seemed largely to follow kabuki's traditions such as stylized fights and poses held a moment to increase tension. The troupe later will perform at Kennedy Center. The most remarkable aspect of <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>'s Kabuki is its leading actor, <PERSON> Ichikawa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who has organized this company of 36 actors and 24 musicians. Two pieces are done at each performance, which lasts three and a half hours, longer than many Americans wish an evening of theater to last. The first is three acts from `` Yoshitsune Senbonzakura,'' an eight-hour, six-act play which was first done in 1747 with puppets and adapted to kabuki the following year. In it, <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON> plays two parts, <PERSON> Tadanobu </PERSON>, a warrior faithful to a hero and a fox who has transformed himself to look like the warrior. The fox did it, the audience learns, to be near <PERSON> Tadanobu </PERSON>'s lover who has a drum made of the skin of his parents. This illustrates fillial piety. <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>, who is 49, is young enough to jump up a flight of steps two at a time, vault off the back of a porch and crawl under it, emerging at the front in white fox fur. But more remarkable than that is the difference in stance the actor has for <PERSON> Tadanobu </PERSON> and for the fox as <PERSON> Tadanobu </PERSON>, when his hands subtly become paws and his head is held less militarily. Some kabuki companies' strongest actors play young women. However, the actor playing <PERSON> Tadanobu </PERSON>'s lover was simpering and whiney. In the second play, `` Kurozuka,'' <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON> played an old woman, actually a demon, whose soul is soothed by a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> priest who says that even demons can find enlightenment. <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON> does a gentle dance in what looks like a corn field, including deep breaths of relief. Then a comic character, played by <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>'s younger brother, blunders and <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON> becomes a demon with red tongue and deep, angry voice. In other kabuki troupes visiting here, older actors have made characters like the old woman more poignant. But <PERSON> Ennosuke </PERSON>'s old woman is n't superficial. One would like to see his troupe again and him again, as he deepens farther in conveying human emotion. Viewers could rent an apparatus to place in one ear, for English summary and commentary, while allowing the rise and fall of the Japanese voices to be heard with the other ear.
</TEXT>
