<HEAD>Paralyzed Woman to Stand up at Wedding</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN HAYWOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KING GEORGE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Cath </PERSON> <PERSON> Tschirn </PERSON> marries <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> on Saturday, she plans to get out of her wheelchair for the first time in five years and stand up to say her vows. With the help of the 2-year-old southeastern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> branch of Volunteers for Medical Engineering, Miss Tschirn -LRB- pronounced Churn -RRB- said she hopes to fulfill her dreams of a fairy tale wedding. `` I got the dress I wanted. If I had n't had the accident, I'd be standing up. Plus, I think I'll shock the whole church,'' she said. The 20-year-old Miss Tschirn was a junior in high school, a cheerleader and a drama club member on Oct. 17, 1984, when the car in which she was riding flipped over. `` All that really happened to me is I was paralyzed,'' she said. `` I did n't have a scratch.'' The organization built a stand for Miss Tschirn to hold herself up, and on the bottom is a lazy susan, which will allow her to turn around and greet the congregation when she and her husband are introduced as Mr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. Founded in 1982 by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Staehlin </PERSON>, the organization has grown from the first club in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> to 400 members and 12 chapters, according to <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Forsythe </PERSON>, its executive director. Ms. <PERSON> Forsythe </PERSON> said <PERSON> Staehlin </PERSON>, an engineer at a defense plant in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, had wanted for years to do something other than defense work. `` He was sitting in church and heard a sermon on using your talents'' and decided to do it, she said. Besides the stand for Miss Tschirn, projects have included software and switches that enable an immobilized person to use a computer by blinking one's eyes; research on an artificial muscle; and voice-controlled videocassette recorders. Using donated funds, the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> chapter bought the materials to make the device for Miss Tschirn, said <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitlock </PERSON>, president of the club and director of maintenance engineering and environmental services at <ORGANIZATION> Riverside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> News </LOCATION>. One club member helped in Miss <PERSON> Tschirn </PERSON>'s rehabilitation and let the group know of the young woman's dream. `` I understand soon after she was injured, she stated it blankly: ` I want to stand up at my wedding,''' <PERSON> Whitlock </PERSON> said. After a yearlong rehabilitation, Miss <PERSON> Tschirn </PERSON> graduated with her high school class. She has regained some movement in her feet. She works, lives in an apartment behind her parents' garage and considers herself more independent than many people who have suffered similar accidents. She also talks to children and anyone who will listen about wearing seat belts, since she was not wearing one when the accident occurred. She met her fiance a year after her accident. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> also was in a car accident and used a wheelchair for three months. `` My fiance said, ` I do n't see why you're so hung up on standing up,''' she recalled. `` ` I did n't meet you standing up.''' Miss Tschirn hopes to leave the wheelchair behind at the altar and sit in another chair for the first part of the ceremony, then stand up for the vows. She and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> will operate the stand, which will be decorated with ribbons and lace. `` I'm going to get him to carry me down the aisle,'' she said.
