<HEAD>Mitchell Blames Bush for Administration Vacancies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> says President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, not the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, is responsible for the 200 vacancies still remaining in top policy-making positions in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attempt to blame the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for foot-dragging is `` unwarranted and unfair,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. In each of the 200 positions, the president has not indicated that holdovers from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration will be asked to stay on, the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democrat told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. There are a total of 432 such jobs. `` Thus, nearly eight months after he took office, the president has failed to make nominations for nearly half of the full-time positions in executive departments and independent agencies which require <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation. `` Whose responsibility is that?'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> asked. `` It is certainly not the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> noted that after he met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Aug. 4 to discuss nominations, White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` The president wanted to express his deep concern that these -LRB- nominations -RRB- were being held up for artificial reasons not related to the candidates themselves.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said that, based on a careful review of the status of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> nominations to date, he is `` urging that the president discontinue such criticism.'' `` It is unfounded and unfair,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` The principal problem is in the slow pace at which nominations are being made, not in the pace at which nominations, once made, are being processed.'' He said there are 48 po