<HEAD>Court Lifts Injunction on Logging in Spotted Owl Habitat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government will seek the resumption of logging in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s old-growth forests, an official said after a federal court lifted its ban on timber-cutting in the northern spotted owl's habitat. Conservationists who sued to prevent lumbering said that while the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>'s unanimous ruling Wednesday removed the overall ban imposed June 7, it still permitted challenges to individual projects. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciliberti </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> spokesman, said 66 million board-feet of timber are ready for sale. The injunction had forbidden timber sales within 2.1 miles of any spotted owl site identified by the bureau. `` We are giving direction for our districts to begin moving those sales that have been enjoined,'' <PERSON> Ciliberti </PERSON> said. If timber sales proceed, conservationists will seek `` endangered species'' status for the owl, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Monteith </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has proposed `` threatened'' status for the bird, a designation which would be weaker than that desired by conservationists. The owl inhabits old-growth forests in western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, mostly on federal land. Scientists view it as a species whose condition indicates a forest's overall health The three-member appeals court rejected conservation groups' chief argument that new information on dangers to the owl's survival was ignored by the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> in its environmental review The panel said the issue could not be raised in a lawsuit because of a federal law backed by the timber industry. However, the court revived sections of the lawsuit contending that destruction of owl habitat by logging violated federal bird protection law and federal and state land-management laws. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutzick </PERSON>, the lawyer for the timber industry's <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said the ruling offered the promise of final victory in the case for loggers and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> communities that depend on logging. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, the lead environmentalst attorney, said: `` It's a disappointment, but the fault is <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' and not the court's. ... We proved that the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> had violated the law, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has said the courts ca n't hear the case.'' The lawsuit challenged the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal in 1987 to conduct a new environmental analysis of hundreds of planned timber sales in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> based on a new study increasing previous predictions of danger to the owl. The bureau contended it already had taken adequate measures to protect the bird. In May, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Frye </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> dismissed the lawsuit, allow