<FIRST>r a PM-BreastCancer     09-07 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Breast Cancer,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Help Predict Early Recurrence of Breast Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By checking cancerous tissue for one protein, doctors believe they can help predict which women with early breast cancer are at high risk of spreading cancer, according to a report published today. Doctors who experimented with this approach found that by testing for the protein, called haptoglobin-related protein, they could identify women who had an extremely high risk of recurrence. They said that the presence of the protein `` appears to be a powerful primary discriminator between clinically aggressive and clinically indolent breast cancers.'' Its prediction power is `` dramatically improved'' when it is combined with information about the sensitivity of the tumors to the hormone progesterone. The research was conducted by Dr. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuhajda </PERSON> and colleagues at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and published in the New England Journal of Medicine. The study was based on 70 patients with early breast cancer who were treated by mastectomy from 1977 through 1985. Doctors checked samples of their tumor tissue for the protein as well as sensitivity to progesterone. Overall, the cancer returned in 31 women. The study found that it recurred in 91 percent of those whose tumors produced the protein but were not sensitive to progesterone. By contrast, it recurred in 24 percent who showed no signs of the hormone but were sensitive to progesterone. Doctors hope that such information will help them identify women who might benefit from aggressive early therapy, such as chemotherapy and mastectomy rather than lump removal.
</TEXT>
