<FIRST>r a PM-Malaria     09-07 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaria,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Therapies Aimed at Blood Vessel Protein May Avert Malaria Complications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New therapy to block malaria infection from harming the brain may result from a study that implicates a protein in that problem and other serious complications of the disease, researchers say. Scientists reported today that red blood cells infected with a malaria-causing parasite stick to the protein, which is found in the inner lining of blood vessels. Attachment of infected red cells to vessel walls is thought to play an important part in producing complications of malaria, said researcher <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON>. For example, it makes red cells clog some blood vessels of the brain. The clogging is a key factor in cerebral malaria, a complication reponsible for more than half the world's deaths from malaria, said scientist <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fajardo </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON> said that if further work demonstrates that the protein plays a key role in cerebral malaria, finding drugs aimed at dislodging the red cells from the protein may prove useful. <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON>, of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Radcliffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and colleagues there describe their work in the British journal Nature. The protein is called intercellular adhesion molecule-1, or ICAM-1. Two other proteins, called CD36 and thrombospondin, had previously been implicated as possible attachment sites for infected red cells. But studies suggested those proteins could not account for all cases of red cell attachment, <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. That led to the work that implicates ICAM-1, and there may be still more blood vessel proteins involved, <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fajardo </PERSON>, a pathology professor at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>, said the findings were very important. Fewer than 1 percent of the world's estimated 100 million to 200 million annual malaria cases are thought to progress to cerebral malaria, but it probably kills more than 500,000 people a year in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> alone, he said. The condition can be treated with quinine, but new drugs would be welcome because quinine does not always work and because it has undesirable side effects, <PERSON> Fajardo </PERSON> said. Malaria occurs after a parasite is injected into the bloodstream from the bite of a mosquito. The Nature paper shows that red blood cells infected by the most dangerous species of malaria parasite, Plasmodium falciparum, can stick to the protein ICAM-1. That protein is widely distributed in the inner linings of capillaries, the tiny blood vessels where red cells can attach themselves in malaria, researchers said. In the test tube, red cells infected by a parasite strain from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> stuck to the ICAM-1 protein on the surface of tissue cells. Red cells infected by a strain from <LOCATION> Gambia </LOCATION> did not. The rate of binding increased after the tissue cells were exposed to tumor necrosis factor, a natural substance known to stimulate production of ICAM-1. <PERSON> Fajardo </PERSON> said that fits in with research that found higher levels of tumor necrosis factor in malaria patients who suffered cerebral malaria than patients who did not. The British researchers are now preparing to test a range of parasite strains to see how widespread the affinity for ICAM-1 is, <PERSON> Berendt </PERSON> said. In the Nature paper, they suggested that the severity of a case of malaria may depend on red cell affinity for various blood vessel proteins, as determined by the infecting parasite, and the infected person's levels of those proteins.
</TEXT>
