<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Yugoslavian </LOCATION> diplomat and a bank chairman have been cleared of conspiring to launder nearly $ 3.5 million provided by undercover agents posing as mobsters, but a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> businessman has been found guilty. <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, an admitted money launderer, testified he lied when he told investigators that 48-year-old <PERSON> Bahrudin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bijedic </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s consul general in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, gave him consular seals, which bar <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials from opening packages, and an official courier letter to help him transport cash to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. `` In 10 years I've represented many not guilty people, but only four innocent men. <PERSON> Bijedic </PERSON> was one of them,'' attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> said. Vinko Mir, 55, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> LBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, also was acquitted of the conspiracy charge, but his bank, a branch of <ORGANIZATION> Ljubljanska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banka </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> was convicted and faces a $ 500,000 fine. Businessman <PERSON> Vjekoslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Spanjol </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Plano </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, was convicted too and faces a sentence of about 60 years in prison and a $ 4.1 million fine, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarmousakis </PERSON> said. Lawyer <PERSON> Denver </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON> said he would appeal Spanjol's conviction <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, the bank's lawyer, could not be reached after the verdict. `` I thought it was entirely possible that he'd be found not guilty on everything. I was surprised he and the bank were found guilty of the conspiracy because he did not have anything to do with the bank or its officers,'' <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON> said. Spanjol, <PERSON> Bijedic </PERSON>, Mir and the bank branch were charged with conspiring to launder $ 3.47 million by depositing the money in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and wiring it back to accounts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to conceal its source. <PERSON> Spanjol </PERSON>, a naturalized citizen, and <ORGANIZATION> LBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> were convicted of conspiracy to obstruct the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury from collecting taxes, gathering accurate information on domestic currency transactions and obtaining information on international cash movements. <PERSON> Spanjol </PERSON> was found guilty of seven other counts, including smuggling out of the country two underwater breathing devices restricted by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The jury acquitted him of two related counts. All three men were arrested Dec. 1, 1988. Cole and Spanjol were apprehended at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> as they tried to ship $ 2 million to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, Customs officials said. Cole, 44, of <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, who had faced up to 230 years in jail and a $ 10.6 million fine, pleaded guilty to money laundering charges and agreed to testify for prosecutors. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Card </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, who could have been sentenced to five years in jail and fined $ 250,000, also pleaded guilty in the case and testified for the government.
