<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseExile     09-07 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Exile,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiled Chinese Student Leader Emerges from Life On The Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An exile's life is not what <PERSON> Wu'er </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaixi </PERSON> wanted, but he took a leading role in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s student uprising last spring and when the dust had settled was on his government's most-wanted list Wu'er, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Normal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, made a dangerous 10-day journey to escape his homeland. Now he's starting over as a student at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, but he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday his eye is still on the battle back home. `` If you experience that kind of massacre it changes your life,'' said Wu'er. `` Whenever I think of my friends who were murdered in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, I feel the obligation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here is now his focus. It's through this hub's telephones, fax machines and computers that he works to effect change back home. In June, the events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> riveted the world and millions saw Wu'er's drawn face as he stood up to Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and demanded a dialogue. Then came the quiet morning after troops stormed the square, killing hundreds, maybe thousands. Only a few who fled could carry on in the wake of such force. He and his girlfriend navigated <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s backroads for 10 days before they finally reached the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and what seemed the only route to go. `` The first step I took was into the sea, and I knew that I would n't go back,'' he said. `` I did n't feel anything because it was just after the massacre and my feelings were already frozen.'' Those few, bloody days last spring also numbed the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people, but they did not cower, Wu'er said. `` This is a famous face now,'' the tall, muscular man said. `` But in the city and in the country, the people protected me. Even people who I did n't know kept quiet and immediately showed support,'' said Wu'er, who tried to find a way out of the country from eight cities before succeeding. The people did n't like the government before, but dislike has been displaced by hatred since their sons and daughters were gunned down in June, Wu'er said. He and many other exiled students, their supporters and those who remain at work underground in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, are getting the word out and forming unions. `` We are n't organized officially, of course, because the government does n't want it,'' said Wu'er, who refused to provide many details on the escape. `` But we can establish a voice outside <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' He said that on a recent trip to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> he helped form a group called <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> as a central organization to coordinate efforts outside of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He said a congress would be held later this month in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to set an agenda and elect a governing board. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest newspaper recently featured Wu'er, complete with various statements about his character _ all derisive. But the insults do n't vex him. `` They're paying a lot of attention to what we're doing outside. And that means they're scared,'' said Wu'er. Wu'er says chance played a large part in his own place in the spotlight. `` When I was a freshman -LRB- in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> -RRB- I loved beer and parties, like <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> kids,'' he said. `` But the political and economic situation forced me to think about the country's system ... `` I stood in the front because I care about my self-worth,'' Wu'er, who will study English in his first semester at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, said through a translator. `` I stood in front because the government does n't allow ... the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people to realize their own self-worth.''
