<HEAD>First House Boarded up at Contaminated Neighborhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's being called Love Canal II and lately a trailer park where toxic contamination was discovered has begun to resemble the infamous toxic waste site just three miles away. A house at the entrance to the Forest <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> trailer park, one of two non-trailers in the subdivision of 53 families, was the first to be boarded up Monday. The house's owner, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>, has relocated to <LOCATION> Lewiston </LOCATION>, about 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> family was one of 23 households in <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Glen </LOCATION> where traces of benzothiazole, a carcinogenic industrial chemical, were found. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the amounts in the homes were so small that they are not a health concern. Nonetheless, the <PERSON> Bauers </PERSON> left a sofa on their front lawn with the words `` Danger Contaminated'' spray-painted on it. Such displays were common 11 years ago when dioxin and other contaminants were discovered at the <LOCATION> Love </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> neighborhood. Eventually, 1,030 families were evacuated from a 10-block area around the former chemical dump site. <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Glen </LOCATION>, home to some of the people who left <LOCATION> Love </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, also was built on a toxic dump. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bauers </PERSON>' property will be padlocked and that a private security force has been hired to patrol the area. Despite the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendation to leave the neighborhood, some residents said they did not want to move away temporarily because they were afraid their homes would be looted. Many homes in Love Canal were vandalized after the evacuations. The dilapidated homes still stand as a monument to environmental disaster, although some have been torn down as part of a plan to revitalize the area. Federal officials have made no determination on the long-term future of <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Glen </LOCATION>. Until residents are out, there can be no excavations to determine the extent of the contamination, officials said. As of Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> had taken 24 applications for temporary relocation, said spokesman <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallowing </PERSON>. Of those, six have moved off-site, eight have found new residences and are waiting to move, and 10 others are still looking. Twenty-three other families are considering moving their trailers out of the park. Six families have not announced plans and are believed to be waiting for the federal buyout, which is expected to take up to a year. <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> said once families moved, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> will board up their homes to protect them from vandalism.
