<SECOND>PM-Marital Sodomy,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Sodomy Law Can't Be Used Against Consenting Couples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY L. CARTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s 156-year-old sodomy law can not be applied to consenting married couples, a judge ruled in clearing a man who spent 18 months in prison for having oral sex with his wife. A lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> lauded the ruling Wednesday as a step toward getting rid of `` this monstrous statute.'' Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Castellani </PERSON> said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>, a 35-year-old carpenter, had been imprisoned illegally. He was serving a two-year term. `` Government has no business with a married couple's private consentual sexual practices,'' <PERSON> Castellani </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>'s `` right to marital and domestic privacy has been violated by the sodomy law as applied to him.'' `` Whew! I feel like someone took a millstone from around my neck,'' said <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>, apparently the first person convicted under the law for conduct between marriage partners. The judge had freed him last week pending a decision. Attorney General <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowers </PERSON> said the state may appeal after an examination of whether the ruling might reach beyond married couples. <PERSON> Bowers </PERSON> said he agreed that the sodomy law can not be applied to consenting married couples. But the prosecutor had argued that the evidence suggested <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>'s wife did not consent to the sodomy. `` I think at least all married couples can celebrate,'' said <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford-Smith </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> lawyer who represented <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>. `` They can bring out the champagne. But there are still a large number of nervous people in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> who are not married.'' <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>'s common-law wife, <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, had accused him of forcing himself on her and she filed a complaint in 1988 that led to <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON> being charged with rape, and aggravated, or forcible, oral and anal sodomy. <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON> denied using force and was acquitted on those counts but was found guilty of the lesser charge of oral sodomy after admitting the couple had oral sex. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law makes oral sex a crime even between consenting adults. The judge said that the jury's acquittal of <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON> on the rape and aggravated sodomy charges meant it believed no force had been involved. <PERSON> Castellani </PERSON> cited a recent <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that upheld application of the sodomy law against homosexuals. The majority decision in that case acknowledged the law might not hold up if applied to married couples.
