<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arlee </PERSON> <PERSON> Andre </PERSON>, creator of the original <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> cake mixes, has died at age 89. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON>, who died Monday, was a cereal chemist testing flour for <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> in 1952 when he decided to develop a cake mix with better flavor and uniformity than the two mixes then commercially available. Working after hours and on his own time, Mr. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> researched the best ways to make yellow cake, white cake, chocolate cake and angel food cake. `` My sister and I were more or less raised on it. We were the test subjects,'' said his son, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON>. `` He'd bring home these little cakes, unfrosted, with little numbers on them. He'd say, ` Taste them and tell me what you think.' `` Of course, we were n't good critics; my sister and I were children and liked them all.'' When the mixes were ready to be marketed, <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> paid food and drink connoisseur <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> a penny a box to use his name. The mixes quickly became popular and were sold to <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Gamble in 1956. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> also moved to the conglomerate and retired from P & amp; G in the mid-1960s. Besides a son and daughter, survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON>, four grandchildren and one great-grandchild. Services will be private.
