<HEAD>Court Hears $810-Million Suit Against Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court today began hearing an $ 810 million lawsuit against <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> based on the former president's tax returns. It is the first case against <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> that has gone to trial in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> since he was ousted three years ago. In all, the government has filed 35 civil suits since in 1987 to recover $ 100 billion that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and 300 associates are accused of stealing during his 24 years in power. He was forced into exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> after a popular-military uprising ousted him in February 1986. Solicitor General <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said he expects to call as many as 20 witnesses and hopes the trial will persuade courts in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and elsewhere to speed up proceedings to recover money <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> allegedly invested abroad. `` This is the first real, significant step toward the recovery of ill-gotten wealth,'' <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said. In the case, being heard in the nation's anti-graft court, the government is seeking $ 476 million in damages and recovery of up to $ 334 million in property <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, allegedly purchased in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Government lawyers said they will argue that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife owned properties worth far more than they could afford based on assets declared in income tax returns. Assistant Solicitor General <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> told the three-judge panel that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' presidential annual salary totaled $ 71,000 for his nearly quarter-century in power. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> earned $ 34,000 during nine years as minister of human settlements and governor of the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, de la <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Eliseo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitargue </PERSON>, intelligence chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION>, testified that between 1960 and 1984, the couple declared total assets equivalent to $ 657,000 at current exchange rates. They paid nearly $ 271,000 in income taxes in that time, <PERSON> Pitargue </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' tax records will `` establish the patently gross and scandalously disproportionate acquisition of Mr. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> on the basis of his declared wealth.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' lawyers, <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Recto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON>, were in the courtroom but told reporters they are not representing the couple. <PERSON> Recto </PERSON> said he will report to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> on the proceedings. `` This is all a big charade,'' <PERSON> Recto </PERSON> told reporters before the proceedings adjourned until Friday. `` This case will take about 100 years more.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> had insisted on his right to defend himself, but the court ruled he forfeited it by ignoring subpoenas delivered to his <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> home. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' successor, has refused to allow him to return, citing national security. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is reported in critical condition at a <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> hospital, where he has been confined since January with heart, kidney and lung failure. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife were indicted by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal grand jury last year on racketeering charges for allegedly pillaging the Philippine treasury and investing some of the money in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> denied the charges and is free on $ 5 million bail. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was temporarily separated from the case because of failing health. The Marcoses have never been charged with a criminal offense in a <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> court because the government fears they would invoke their constitutional right to return to face their accusers.
