<FIRST>r a PM-MBTASuit     09-07 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MBTA Suit,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>MBTA Settles Suit Over Racial Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city transit agency has agreed to pay at least $ 689,000 to the estate and children of a black man who was struck and killed by a subway train after being chased into a station by a gang of whites in 1982. The settlement was reached in July and made public Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> in response to a Freedom of Information Act request by The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a 30-year-old janitor, died after fleeing a group of white men who chased him in the city's <LOCATION> Dorchester </LOCATION> section. In 1985, two men were convicted of manslaughter and three of assault in the attack. The settlement stemmed from a $ 10 million negligence and wrongful-death suit filed by the mothers of <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>'s children, ages 10 and 19. The suit alleged that <ORGANIZATION> MBTA </ORGANIZATION> workers neglected to notify police immediately when <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> and a friend fled into the station and failed to alert train operators that <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> had run onto the tracks. The suit also claimed that the train that hit <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> was operating without headlights. The <ORGANIZATION> MBTA </ORGANIZATION> also agreed to pay $ 138,000 to <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>'s estate, of which some will go to his children. The agency will also pay the children at least $ 551,000 in installments for the rest of their lives, the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> said today. The children are <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>'s sole heirs because their mothers never married him. <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> was walking along a street around 12:30 a.m. with a white friend, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, when a group of whites began shouting racial epithets, hurling bottles and threatening to kill the pair, authorities said. The suit claimed that <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Davulis </PERSON>, a coin changer, failed to call police when <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> ran into the station and called for help. It was not until <PERSON> Davulis </PERSON> saw <PERSON> Grady </PERSON> punched that he finally called for help, the suit alleged. <PERSON> Davulis </PERSON> called police a second time after he was initially placed on hold but left for home before police arrived, the suit said. <ORGANIZATION> MBTA </ORGANIZATION> police arrived seven minutes later, looked around, saw no one, and left, the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> reported.
