<HEAD>U.S. Television May `Invade' Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, By the, with 2 grafs to show the types of
programs that could be broadcast to Cuba. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Proponents
say.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is planning to use what may be the ultimate weapon against <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>: television. By the end of the year, a million or more Soviet-made TV sets are expected to tune in six hours a day, seven days a week to American-made news programs and the best reruns <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> has to offer, courtesy of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Could programs such as `` Dynasty,'' `` Days of Our Lives'' and pro bowling lure big <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> audiences away from state-run TV? Proponents say Cubans will flock to their sets, as they apparently did with <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>, and take their first uncensored look at the outside world in 30 years. But critics say TV Marti may harden anti-American attitudes in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, violate international communications laws and cause massive headaches for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> broadcasters who may find themselves blacked out by TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>'s powerful signal or who may be bludgeoned by retaliatory broadcasts from <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supports sending TV to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, as do many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and Cuban exile groups. But the plan has faced some powerful opponents, including Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>. After three years of rancorous debate over the wisdom of such an enterprise, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this year voted money to begin TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> testing this fall. But the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, before it appropriated $ 7.5 million in July for a 90-day TV Marti test, agreed to hold up funds for full operation until the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> holds hearings on whether TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> would violate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> treaty obligations. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earlier authorized $ 32 million for <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> over the next two years, and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measures are awaiting resolution in conference committee. If the spending plan gains final congressional approval, the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> will begin satellite relays of Spanish-language programs from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to a receiving station in Cudjoe Key, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. There, weather permitting, the signals will be fed to a transmitter aboard a giant balloon tethered two miles above the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, and thence to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> some 90 miles away. Cubans, TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> backers say, are eagerly awaiting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television. `` My understanding is they ca n't wait for it to start,'' <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Cuban-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Wednesday. `` Radio <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> has, and hopefully TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> will as well, provide views to the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> people that they are not receiving.'' <PERSON> Tillman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> has helped nurture human rights groups, made the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> populace aware of the number of Cuban army casualties in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, the level of oppression in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, AIDS and the new era of openness in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION>. `` All that news is frequently censored by the Cuban government media, so the promise of TV Marti, with pictures, is very important,'' she said. Cuban officials have labeled TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> `` anti-Cuban propaganda'' and said they will take appropriate measures against it. When Radio <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> was launched in May 1985, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> briefly tried to jam the broadcasts. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> has lobbied against <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION>, saying it could wreak havoc on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stations, which already are subject to periodic radio blasts from enormously powerful Cuban transmitters. `` The idea is technically flawed and there are no provisions to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> broadcasters from either direct interference from TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>'s signal or retaliatory broadcasts from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> NAB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Wurfel </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has demonstrated in the past it has powerful transmitters that can cause interference to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> radio stations'' from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and as far west as <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wurfel </PERSON> said. Some Cuban-American groups also oppose TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cuban-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, wrote recently in a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> op-ed piece that TV <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> violates a 1982 treaty that stipulates that normal TV transmission wavelengths are for domestic, national use only. `` The creation of TV Marti would surely be perceived by <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> as a hostile act,'' <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said. `` The Cuban community in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> will suffer the brunt of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s displeasure, as we did after <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>, when <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> virtually closed off all family visits to the island.''
