<HEAD>Bush Goes on the Road to Promote Drug Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New throughout from Bush speeches in Baltimore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today praised `` the courage and determination'' of the government of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> for extraditing an accused major drug trafficker to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and warned against letting critics of his anti-narcotics strategy `` lose the war.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, addressing the annual convention of the American Legion, appealed to the veterans to rally behind his anti-drug and anti-crime measures to help `` free our country from the fear of drugs and crime.'' The president, recalling a now-famous campaign gaffe he made ast last year's Legion convention, also jokingly told the veterans to `` remember <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> shocked the convention on Sept. 7, 1988, by saying it was Pearl Harbor Day. The day actuall is Dec. 7. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the extradition Wednesday of <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>, indicted in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on charges of laundering money for the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> drug cartel, `` sends a strong signal of the courage and determination of President <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government to deal with this scourge which drugs are inflicting on all of us.'' He said his $ 7.9 billion anti-drug package, unveiled in a speech to the nation Tuesday night, `` will require the bravery and sacrifice that Americans have shown before and must again.'' `` As veterans, you know how battles are often fought, house by house, block by block. Well, we'll win this battle the same way. We're going to win win it kid by kid, neighborhood by neighborhood,'' said the president. Democrats have charged the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> drug plan is underfunded and inadequate to meet the menace. To them, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> replied, `` Some, incredibly, say it's not enough. This from the very people who oppose the death penalty. It's that kind of thinking that's lost too many battles. `` So let's not let these critics lose the war,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I ask you to support our crime plan and also the other parts of our drug strategy.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who entered the convention hall wearing his <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> 77 cap from his hometown of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, also attacked the House-passed defense authorization bill and commended the Legion's support of his call for a constitutional amendment to protect the flag Legion officials presented him with petitions signed by a million people in support of a constitutional amendment. He said the House-passed $ 295 billion defense budget `` is totally unacceptable to the commander-in-chief of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> armed forces.'' He charged that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version, now headed for compromising with a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> defense bill, would `` strip money from programs crucial'' to modernizing strategic weapons, including the mobile Midgetman missile and putting the MX missile on rail cars. Recalling his campaign gaffe, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` Today surprisingly is Sept. 7. Can you believe it? And I'm determined not to repeat the mistake I made exactly one year ago when I referred to this as Pearl Harbor Day. ... As long as I live I'll remember the gasp from the audience.'' From the convention. the president went to nearby <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> for a ceremony marking the 175th anniversary of the Battle of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in the War of 1812 against the British, which inspired <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Key </PERSON> to write `` The Star-Spangled Banner.'' Standing before a 90-foot white flagpole, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called it `` one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most hallowed shrines.'' He said <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> `` stopped a British invasion and preserved our independence'' in `` one of the greatest chapters in the American experience.'' The speeches in the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> area kicked off a series of out-of-town appearances to drum up support for the anti-drug strategy. On Friday he heads to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to deliver the same message. Although the drug plan does n't call for direct use of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, it proposes sending some drug offenders to military-style boot camps. In addition, the administration is seriously considering using <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> forces for marijuana eradication, said drug policy director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a series of appearances Wednesday in behalf of his program, struck back at Democrats who attacked his program. While apologizing for getting `` down into the trenches of domestic politics,'' he told an audience that included a group of Latin American ambassadors: `` I could n't help but notice that the minute I finished speaking, there was the predictable response by some that we have n't done enough.'' On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, some Democrats pushed the case for raising taxes to finance an all-out fight against narcotics with Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., declaring: `` Unless the president supports the tax increases that will be necessary to fight this war, the drug dealers are going to win. House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., said that `` without the administration's support, the idea of raising taxes is futile. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has rejected new taxes.
