<HEAD>British Hooligans Hustled Out of Sweden</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Thatcher quote, ferry refusing passage
to some Britons, raises news report of attack near train station. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedish police hustled hundreds of English soccer hooligans out of the country today after they ransacked shops and scuffled with rowdy Swedish youths. Police said 102 Britons and 106 Swedes were arrested before and after Wednesday's World Cup qualifying match, which ended in a 0-0 draw. Duty officer <PERSON> Lennart </PERSON> <PERSON> Norden </PERSON> said 78 people spent the night in jail. Newspapers ran a picture of two youths, one with a raised club in his hand, kicking a man outside a <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> train station. Dozens of people looked on. A few Britons and Swedes may be charged with assault and vandalism, but nearly all the foreigners have been freed and given 48 hours to leave <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, said Superintendent <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Nilsson </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> called the fans' behavior `` a disgrace to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>,'' and her government asked soccer officials to cancel a visit by the national team to the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> in December `` I am always horrified if there is any difficulty with football fans abroad,'' she said. Scandinavian Seaways said today it refused passage to about 20 Britons, fearing violence. It bought back return tickets from one group and volunteered to pay for 10 people to find another way home. `` We did n't want them on board,'' said a spokesman. The shipping line said it confiscated passports of another 30 passengers, and threatened to turn over the documents to British police if there was any problem at sea. About 600 policemen at the <LOCATION> Rasunda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> kept the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> fans isolated in a standing terrace during the game. Dozens of visitors were escorted directly from the stadium to trains for the west coast ports of <LOCATION> Goteborg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Helsingborg </LOCATION> for the return ferry to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Swedes and Britons clashed later in town, but no serious injuries were reported. The trouble `` was less than we expected,'' said police Superintendent <PERSON> Sture </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoglund </PERSON>. One newspaper headline read: `` Police Win the Match.'' Earlier, about 100 <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> supporters, mostly teen-agers, rampaged through downtown <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, throwing bottles at police vehicles, knocking down passers-by and vandalizing shops. One large group of youngsters entered the Ahlens department store, overturning flower pots and goods displays. Some looting also was reported, <PERSON> Norden </PERSON> said. `` No more,'' wrote sports commentator <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Thylin </PERSON> in the Aftonbladet daily. `` This problem seems insoluble. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> must be shut out of the European soccer community.'' The hooliganism could effect a decision by the European soccer clubs' governing body, <ORGANIZATION> UEFA </ORGANIZATION>, to lift a ban against English clubs playing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The ban was imposed after <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> supporters were blamed for a riot that triggered a stampede in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, killing 39 spectators. The ban does not apply to the national team. On Monday a British fan died when he jumped off a ferry into the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Under the influence of drugs, he panicked when companions sprayed him with a fire extinguisher. Fears of hooliganism prompted the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to ask its Swedish counterpart to cut back ticket sales in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. About 1,000 visitors attended the match at <LOCATION> Rasunda </LOCATION>, which was filled to its 38,500-seat capacity.
