<HEAD>Khomeini's Son Rules Out Relations with United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The son of the late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> today ruled out relations between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s new president, <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, is undoubtedly anti-American. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, 43, appeared to be trying to rally radicals against conciliatory moves toward the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> expected from <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who is associated with the so-called pragmatist camp in postwar <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Hatred of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, referred to in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as the `` Great Satan,'' is strong among radicals who favor maintaining revolutionary Islamic fervor. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> as saying: `` You know well the higher authorities of the country and our dear president. If our president is not anti-American, who in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is?'' He spoke at a meeting with families of soldiers who died in the eight-year <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> added that <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> `` is not a person to take even one step outside the path of the imam, and against his guidance,'' the radio reported. Iranians regarded <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> as a supreme spiritual leader, or imam. Before his death on June 3, he preached a staunchly anti-American doctrine that ruled out any ties with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. His son's description of <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s anti-American credentials would seem to make any friendly gesture toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> more difficult. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, elected July 28, is known to want to shed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s radical image abroad, to end <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s international isolation, and to attract foreign investment and technology to rebuild the country's war-battered economy <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> recently won parliamentary approval for a 22-man Cabinet consisting largely of technocrats, many Western-educated, and his administration is making positive gestures to ease strains with some foes. Earlier this week, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Besharati </PERSON>, said 16 Western hostages, including eight Americans, being held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem groups could be freed if <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> releases billions of dollars in frozen Iranian assets. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has made the release of the hostages a condition for improving ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The younger <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> used to act as a spokesman for his father and was expected to become part of the senior leadership when his father died. But he has no official role and is considered more of a symbol for the hard-line elements with which he has allied himself.
