<HEAD>Senators Want Aid, Experts Sent to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the world's industrial democracies should send economic, business and labor experts to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to help that nation's new non-communist government establish a free economy, Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> explained his proposal as other lawmakers urged the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to expand the modest package of aid it has earmarked for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as a critical signal of political support. <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> said the team of experts he envisions would make a complete but speedy survey of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s largely state-controlled economy and recommend basic changes needed to spur investment and free enterprise. Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said many of the Polish leaders he spoke with when he visited <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> last month asked for just such help. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leaders, including its communist leaders, are wide open to new American investment,'' said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is considering ways to expand the $ 100 million aid package the president announced in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> earlier this summer. `` I am convinced we can take some additional steps at no cost and perhaps also find some additional resources within existing budgets and programs,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. He said although <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> needs long-term help, especially to ease the strain caused by payments on its $ 39 billion foreign debt, short-term aid is essential. `` There can not be a long-term approach unless <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s government makes it through the short term,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` That's where an immediate American signal of support can be critical.'' `` We in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and our allies in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, have a big security, political and economic stake in what happens in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` If Solidarity remains in power and succeeds in governing, the threat of war in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will go down, democratization in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and even in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> itself will get a big boost, and the prospects for expanded private investment in and trade with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> will grow,'' he said. Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., urged support for his three-step plan to send <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> introduced legislation Wednesday which would postpone interest payments on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s $ 2.8 billion debt to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks for three years and defer half of the interest payments due in the following two years. The proposal also calls for establishment of an investment fund to distribute $ 300 million for development projects in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for each of three years. It would also call for spending $ 25 million to help <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> modernize its telephone system.
