<HEAD>Gabrielle Veers Away From U.S. Mainland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with noon positions, wind speed dropping
to 105 mph. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A huge but weaker Hurricane Gabrielle should skirt <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> sometime after midnight with high winds and big ocean swells, but the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> will get little more than heavy surf, forecasters said today. Forecasters said it appeared the storm center would pass 200 to 300 miles east of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, far enough away for the island to escape destructive tropical storm-force winds. Swells of more than 20 feet were reported in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> this morning. `` They'll get some showers, some winds and definitely some surf problems,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday night. <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON>'s top sustained winds dropped from a high of 135 mph to 105 mph as it swirled north on a path far from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but the storm was so large that swells of five to 13 feet were recorded more than 1,500 miles away, from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` We have a very large wind field around this hurricane,'' Sheets said. Winds 39 mph or higher _ a speed that forecasters define as tropical storm-force _ stretched 250 miles to the west and 300 miles to the east as <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> curved north in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION>. At noon EDT, <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON>'s center was located near 29.9 degrees north latitude and 60.0 degrees west longitude, or about 320 miles east-southeast of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. It was heading north at 15 mph. <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> is the largest and most powerful hurricane of the season, rating just below last year's Hurricane Gilbert, which ravaged the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> with 155 mph winds. Far to the north of <LOCATION> Gabrielle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> maintained its status as a minimal hurricane, with winds of 75 mph. The storm was drifting slowly out in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and was no threat to land, forecasters said. At noon EDT, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>'s center was near 39.5 degree north latitude and 48.0 degrees west longitude, or about 900 miles west of the <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION>. It was drifting north at 7 mph. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> is the sixth and <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> the seventh named storm of the 1989 Atlantic hurricane season. Storms are named when their winds reach 39 mph and are classified as hurricanes when they grow to 74 mph.
