id four officers joined to beat a woman waiting for a bus with whips. `` She was jumping up and down. Then she ran and they chased after her,'' <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON>. `` One of them even fell and then got up again and chased her, hitting her. Their was an elderly man -LRB- who -RRB- collapsed because of the beating.'' As the local crime prevention officer, <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON> said he had tried to defuse trouble by telling the students they could `` do their thing'' and then disperse in 20 minutes. He said he took one riot squad out of view of the students, but that another squad repeatedly charged into `` the normal curious crowds,'' including shoppers. `` They were just hitting people. They could n't care if they were innocent bystanders or not,'' <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON> said. `` They were running after them even when they were fleeing, hitting them. `` It seemed to me that they were enjoying themselves, feasting on the people. ` You could just see the killer instinct in their eyes.'' <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> police Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Phillipus </PERSON> <PERSON> Fourie </PERSON> confirmed that <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON> had been summoned to his office Wednesday to discuss police matters but he would not comment further. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON> could face retaliation, but that he was `` going to be given very wide recognition in the black community'' for his willingness to describe police action.
