<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is suing to overturn an <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> ordinance barring `` nuclear weapons work'' in the city. The ordinance _ one of the few such nuclear-free ordinances not considered symbolic among about 160 in the country _ unconstitutionally interferes with national defense, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in a lawsuit filed Wednesday in federal court. The ordinance could force two federal installations employing 2,170 people to leave <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION>, the department said. They are the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which supplies <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> ships with components for nuclear weapons, and a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> operations office overseeing weapons research at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> east of <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, primary author of the ballot initiative, said the measure approved by voters in November was drafted to exclude the Naval Supply Center, where more than 2,000 people work. And City Attorney <PERSON> Jayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the ban on nuclear weapons work covered such activities as `` creating nuclear weapons in their offices,'' and should not apply to an administrative office like the DOE's. The lawsuit said the Constitution gives the federal government exclusive authority over defense. The lawsuit also said the Atomic Energy Act gives the federal government sole authority over nuclear weapons and nuclear energy. The ballot initiative's sponsors countered that local communities also have rights. `` We should be able to exercise the full power of local governments to protect our health and safety and to direct policy about what happens in our city jurisdictions,'' said <PERSON> Madge </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON> of the Nuclear-Free <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> added that the First Amendment should take precedence. `` The people of an entire city are saying, we do n't want this going on. The federal government is saying, you have no right to say that. That ceases to be democracy,'' <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, the city attorney, called <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear-free ordinance one of the broadest in the country. Among other things, it bans nuclear weapons work in the city in two years. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said she believed it was the first such ordinance the federal government has challenged. A conservative legal group filed a federal lawsuit challenging it four months ago.
