<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> air force pilot who flew a MiG-19 jet to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> said Thursday he defected because of his contempt for the Communist government after its suppression of a movement for democracy. Lt. <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Wen-hao </PERSON>, 24, told reporters he sympathizes with the soldiers who carried out the crackdown in June, saying they had to follow government orders. `` I do n't want to dedicate my blood and my life to a Communist regime that the people spit on in contempt,'' said <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON>. For the defection, <LOCATION> Taiwain </LOCATION> will pay him 206 pounds of gold worth about $ 880,000. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has a sliding scale of gold rewards for <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military defectors, calculated on the type of aircraft they bring out. <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> flew his Soviet-built fighter to the Nationalist-held island of <LOCATION> Quemoy </LOCATION> on Wednesday from <LOCATION> Longxi </LOCATION> airport in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s southern <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> province, just over a mile away The flight took 14 minutes. He was brought to <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> on Thursday for a news conference and told reporters he had planned to defect for two years but was spurred to action by the June crackdown on the student-led democracy movement at Tiananmen Square in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. After taking off, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> said he kept the fighter low to escape pursuing aircraft, but the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> air force apparently did not notice he had left. `` I was so nervous that I did n't know if anyone followed me,'' he said. `` I could still hear the air base's communications when I landed at <LOCATION> Quemoy </LOCATION> airport.'' <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> said he left his parents, a sister, and his grandmother behind. In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign 