<HEAD>House Votes to Reward Hungary's Economic Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, eager to reward <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for its steps toward economic openness and human rights, voted Thursday to grant the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nation a three-year extension of preferential trade status. The 221-169 vote, over the objection of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, sent the matter to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bill would grant an extension through July 4, 1992, of the most-favored-nation trading status <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> currently enjoys on a year-to-year basis. Sponsors of the bill said it was time to reward <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s moves toward a more Western-style market economy and relatively open emigration policies. `` For 25 years they have fought the communists, and they have turned that country around, and we have not done a damn thing to help them,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the Ways and Means trade subcommittee The original measure would have provided a five-year extension, but that was scaled back in a compromise with opponents, primarily conservative Republicans, who argued the gesture infringes on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s right to conduct foreign policy and diminishes pressure on <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to keep the reforms going `` Let us remember that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> remains a member in good standing of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, speaking against the provision. `` This bill is an embarrassment to the people of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> who have been fighting for their freedom. They want the pressure kept on their government to allow them to live where they want to live, work where they want to work, move where they want to move,'' he said. `` This is a fairly delicate time,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulze </PERSON>, R-Pa., who helped work out the three-year compromise `` I do n't think we should let the emotional euphoria -LRB- over Hungarian reform -RRB- carry us into a policy we might regret. The five-year version of the bill had been rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in June when it failed to muster the two-thirds majority needed under the expedited floor procedure used to bring it before the chamber. At the time, opponents argued that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was about to travel to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, and planned to annouce his own rewards for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. During his trip, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared `` the Iron Curtain has begun to part'' and promised new trade benefits and a $ 25 million grant to spur free enterprise. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would be inclined to grant permanent most-favored-nation status, which offers the best tariff rates available, if <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> adopts a liberalized emigration law now under consideration. Current law bars most-favored-nation status to communist countries with restrictive emigration policies. Since the ban was imposed in 1974, three nations have been granted waivers: <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` The president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> went over there and put his Good Housekeeping seal of approval on it,'' argued Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., speaking for the bill `` This is a country that has proven over and over again that it wants to be free, open and democratic.''
