want to go in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,'' he said. An estimated 1 million people have died in the 28 years that the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has been fighting for independence. <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, a former Italian colony, is a province of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and contains the troubled East African nation's only direct access to the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. The Carter Center, which houses the presidential library, a museum, a think tank and foundations working for peace and public health, is trying to fill a gap by acting as go-between in the dispute. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> intervention is limited to disputes between nations. `` These are very intransigent, difficult, dividing issues that have never been addressed in a substantive way before,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said recently. `` Of course my hope is, my expectation is, that we'll go from there to fairly sustained talks that might bring about a cease-fire.'' During his presidency, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> served as a go-between in the Camp David talks that led to an accord between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. The Atlanta Constitution reported today that <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> has been asked by both sides to serve as mediator if the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> talks lead to further negotiations. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> succeeded <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, who took part in the Camp David accords. Exactly when such long-term talks on <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> would be held and who would oversee them are matters the delegations hope to decide in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has said.
