<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today approved 83-8 legislation shifting $ 45 million used for congressional mailings to a drug treatment program aimed at helping drug-addicted mothers and their babies. The lopsided vote came over strong opposition from Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, who accused its backers of political posturing at the expense of lawmaker communications with constituents. Republicans proposed the measure Wednesday, the day after President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced a $ 7.9-billion anti-drug abuse campaign _ aimed at transferring the money from the account legislators use for their mailings. The provision was offered as an amendment to a bill providing $ 2 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' own expenses for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. The proposal all but eliminates district-wide mailings used often by senators and representatives to keep their names in their constituents' minds, but it allows members to continue answering individual queries. Critics said the mass mailings provided taxpayer-financed publicity to incumbents, making them difficult to defeat. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> had said Wednesday that such a dramatic cut in congressional mailings to constituents would deprive Alaskans of an important source of news. He said many Alaskans get no daily newspapers and learn of news from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> only from radio and brief television broadcasts. `` We send out a postal patron newsletter to people who have no other source of information about what's going on in the nation's capital,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> told his colleagues But <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> lured few senators to his cause during today's debate, although Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., did say he thought the amendment was `` not in the national interest Seven Democrats and one Republican voted against the amendment. They were: <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Spark </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, D-N.Y. and the Republican, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> Nine senators did not vote. Final action on the appropriations bill was put off until later in the day. The measure was proposed by Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., a supporter of tougher efforts against drug abuse, a longtime critic of the burgeoning costs of legislators' mailings and a candidate for governor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> `` What we are faced with is the opportunity to not spend on newsletters, and instead to put this money into one of the least well-funded'' drug programs, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. The money would go to a program started in 1988 that provides treatment to drug-addicted pregnant women, focusing on those who use crack. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said 400,000 babies are born annually to mothers who use drugs. In his Tuesday evening speech unveiling the $ 7.9 billion drug campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed spending $ 300 million for treatment programs. He listed initiatives to help pregnant drug users as part of the effort, but did n't specifically say how much should be spent for them. Without <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s amendment, the legislative spending bill would limit congressional spending on mail next year to $ 80 million: $ 48 million for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which has 435 members, and $ 32 million for the 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bill would also reduce from six to two the number of district-wide mailings permitted each year, except for notices of town meetings. Legislators could send more, but would have to pay for them out of the funds each receives for general office expenses. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is on track to spend $ 53.9 million on its mail this year, but those expenses traditionally skyrocket during election years, which 1990 happens to be. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed a $ 1.6 billion version of the legislative spending bill July 31 that would provide $ 124.7 million for congressional mailings. House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators will have to find a compromise to their differences over congressional mail before the bill can be sent to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature.
