<HEAD>Sri Lankan Leader Invites Sinhalese, Tamil Rebels For Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has invited Sinhalese and Tamil rebels for peace talks with all political parties in a bid to end ethnic wars in which 16,000 people have been killed, officials said Thursday. Military officials said the latest violence, largely inspired by Sinhalese radicals of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, had claimed 32 lives since Wednesday. The Sinhalese group is an ultranationalist guerrilla organization that has waged a campaign of assassinations and strikes to topple President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s government. <PERSON> Bradman </PERSON> <PERSON> Weerakoon </PERSON>, the president's foreign affairs adviser, told reporters the government invited the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and leaders of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 23 recognized parties to the proposed peace conference Sept. 13. `` We have positive responses from 10 parties. We have not received a single negative response. So for all intents and purposes there is a general acceptance of the government's invitation,'' said <PERSON> Weerakoon </PERSON>. He said the Sinhalese radicals are not among the 10 who have accepted, but they have not rejected the invitation. The group has rejected all previous peace overtures. <PERSON> Weerakoon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> also had invited the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, a dominant separatist group, and other former Tamil militant groups. Most groups of the minority Tamils ended their battle for an independent nation in the northeast two years ago following an accord that promised Tamils limited autonomy. But the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> reneged on the peace plan and began attacking <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> peacekeeping soldiers deployed to supervise the accord, which was signed June 29, 1987. At least 1,000 soldiers have died in the fighting. At least 10,000 other people have been killed in the Tamil war. Most of the deaths occurred between 1983, when the Tamils took up arms, and 1987, when the accord was signed. After Tamil agitation subsided, Sinhalese radicals in the south and center of the island began fighting to protest the accord, which they said gives too many concessions to the minority Tamils, and an Indian troop presence they charge compromises <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s sovereignty Tamils form 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese who make up 75 percent of the population and control the government. Most Tamils are Hindu, while Sinhalese are mainly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION>. The government says at least 5,000 people have died in the Sinhalese rebellion and blames the radicals for most deaths. The radicals say the military and pro-government vigilante groups are responsible for the killings. Among the 32 people killed in the latest violence were three soldiers blown up in a land mine blast Thursday, and another shot by Sinhalese extremists who ambushed troops bathing in a stream, the military officials said. They said they did not know who planted the land mine.
