<HEAD>House Defense Bill `Totally Unacceptable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> denounced a House-passed defense bill as `` totally unacceptable to the commander in chief'' on Thursday and accused the chamber of holding the defense budget hostage to $ 20 billion in `` unneeded programs.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a speech to the American Legion that mixed defense and anti-drug themes, also praised Wednesday's decision by <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> president <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> to extradite a major drug figure to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The extradition of <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> to face <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug money-laundering charges `` sends a strong signal of the courage and determination of President <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government to deal with the scourge which drugs are inflicting on all of us,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Declaring `` Remember <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also poked fun at his 1988 campaign gaffe _ to the same group one year ago _ confusing Pearl Harbor Day. `` Today, surprisingly, is Sept. 7. Can you believe it? And I'm determined not to repeat the mistake I made exactly one year ago when I referred to this as Pearl Harbor Day. A year ago, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a World War II combat veteran, told the American Legion convention in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>: `` I wonder how many Americans remember that today is Pearl Harbor Day.'' The Japanese air attack on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval base in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> occurred Dec. 7, 1941. The president, moving from drugs to defense, said Americans deserve protection from both `` the fear of war abroad -LRB- and -RRB- the fear of drugs and crime at home.'' But he claimed that the national defense was threatened by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version of a defense spending bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. A House-Senate conference committee begins work on a compromise version Friday. While suggesting he could live with the Senate-passed bill, which preserves most of the administration's programs, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared: `` The House version is totally unacceptable to the commander in chief of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> armed forces.'' Congressional negotiators must reconcile rival versions of the legislation to authorize $ 295 billion in <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending and $ 10 billion for defense programs in the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> refused to fully fund either of the two types of mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants. It chopped in half, to $ 502 million from $ 1.1 billion, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s request for the rail-based multiple-warhead MX; and it deleted all funds for the single-warhead Midgetman. The House bill `` contains unneeded programs costing nearly $ 20 billion from 1990 to 1994, holding our defense budget hostage to projects that will strip money from programs crucial to strategic modernization,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Fellow veterans, real peace is not an accident, so let us modernize our strategic forces and thus encourage arms control,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The president, a longtime <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> member, wore a cap from his home post _ Post 77 in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> _ at the beginning and end of his appearance, although removing it for the speech. On drugs, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his $ 7.9 billion anti-drug package, unveiled in a speech to the nation Tuesday, `` will require the bravery and sacrifice that Americans have shown before and must again.'' `` As veterans, you know how battles are often fought, house by house, block by block. Well, we'll win this battle the same way. We're going to win win it kid by kid, neighborhood by neighborhood,'' he said. To critics of the plan, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` Some, incredibly, say it's not enough This from the very people who oppose the death penalty. It's that kind of thinking that's lost too many battles. `` So let's not let these critics lose the war,'' he added. `` I ask you to support our crime plan and also the other parts of our drug strategy.'' Afterwards, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> attended a ceremony at nearby <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McHenry </LOCATION> marking the 175th anniversary of the War of 1812 battle against the British that inspired <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Key </PERSON> to write `` The Star-Spangled Banner.'' Standing before a 90-foot white flagpole, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called the fort `` one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most hallowed shrines'' and said its small force of soliders had `` stopped a British invasion and preserved our independence.'' While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> used his appearance before the American Legion to promote his drug plan and criticize the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s defense bill, one Republican lawmaker suggested using money for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s B-2 stealth bomber to fund the anti-drug effort. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> said he will introduce legislation next week to cancel all procurement money authorized by the House for the stealth bomber in fiscal 1990 and transfer the funds to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s anti-drug program. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in approving its version of the defense bill last month, authorized procurement of two stealth bombers, which at a cost of $ 530 million apiece are considered the most expensive planes in history.
