<HEAD>Four Ill, One Critically After Eating Poisonous Wild Mushrooms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One man remained in critical condition Thursday after he and three other people ate what experts described as the deadliest species of wild mushroom. `` It's the worst outbreak of amanita mushroom poisoning in at least 20 years,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, medical director of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The victims ate the amanita phalloides in two incidents Friday, one near <LOCATION> Siren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and the other by <LOCATION> Gull </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Brainerd </LOCATION>. All were taken to <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul-Ramsey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. An unidentified 52-year-old man from <LOCATION> Isanti </LOCATION> was in critical condition. He had picked mushrooms Friday evening near <LOCATION> Siren </LOCATION> and cooked them into a creamed soup-like mixture that he shared with a friend, <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON>, 32, of <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>. The man ate about two bowls of the mushroom mixture; <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> ate just a little, and she was released from the hospital Tuesday. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said the man had liver failure. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Padrnos </PERSON>, 59, and his wife <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON>, 52, who own the <LOCATION> Gull </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> Four Seasons Resort just north of <LOCATION> Brainerd </LOCATION>, were the other victims. <PERSON> Padrnos </PERSON> was discharged from the hospital Wednesday; his wife remained in the hospital and was improving steadily. The cases prompted health and plant experts to issue warnings about eating mushrooms picked in the wild. Mushrooms have flourished in the recent cool, wet weather and will be plentiful through early October, said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a plant pathologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. Only those who have been trained should pick mushrooms, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. Amanita phalloides and its relatives resemble the edible field mushroom. <PERSON> Padrnos </PERSON> said he had some doubts about the safety of the mushrooms as he sliced them into a frying pan. `` They did n't seem just right,'' he said. `` So I fried them for a long time, 15 minutes. Dumb me, I did n't throw them out.'' <PERSON> Padrnos </PERSON> said he and his wife scooped the fried mushrooms onto pork chops and ate them. The last recorded amanita death in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> occurred in 1960, but there have been several non-fatal cases since then, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. Amanita phalloides contain amatoxin, a deadly poison that keeps recycling through the body, damaging the liver and sometimes the kidneys. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said there is no antidote for the toxin.
