<HEAD>Iraq Says Explosion Killed 19, Not Hundreds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Iraqi Embassy said Thursday that 19 people died in an explosion at a fuel depot outside <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, contradicting reports by British media and Kurdish dissidents that at least 700 people died and that the site was a top-secret missile plant. The embassy said 19 firefighters and civil defense workers fighting a fire at a depot containing `` highly flammable gasoline materials'' were killed when a passing truck packed with explosives detonated. In a statement, the embassy said all the casualties were Iraqi nationals, and that a small number of workers suffered minor cuts when the explosion shattered the windows of passing buses. The fire was put out in a few hours, it said. The embassy said the truck was en route to a dam under construction in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and its explosives were `` for use in engineering projects.'' An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION>, an outlawed Kurdish movement fighting the <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> government, quoted sources in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on Wednesday as saying 700 bodies had been recovered. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Independent newspaper, quoting unidentified diplomats and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> sources, also reported at least 700 people were killed, including Egyptian engineers helping the Iraqis develop a new ballistic missile. The embassy denied that a modified version of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s medium-range Condor-2 surface-to-surface missile known as the Badr-2000 was being developed `` between <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and any other country including <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>,'' as news reports had said `` <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has already proved being self-sufficient in its technological capabilities, and it has produced middle-range missiles by developing a technology that is not yet available to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> itself,'' the statement said. The embassy gave no further details about the facility between <LOCATION> Al-Hillah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ad-Diwaniyeh </LOCATION>, about 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, which dissidents described as a top-secret missile plant. An embassy employee who answered telephone calls said the embassy was closed and no officials were available for comment.
