<HEAD>State Department Says Quarter-Million Soviets May Seek Entry In 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimated Thursday that up to 250,000 Soviet citizens will apply for admission to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1990. `` We are seeking ways to fairly and equitably respond to the expansion in demand,'' spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. About half the applicants are Jews. Armenians comprise another large category, as do Pentecostal Christians. The spokeswoman denied published reports that because of the heavy flow some Soviet Jews would be declared ineligible. This would have the effect of diverting many of them to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was instrumental in persuading the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to lower is immigration barriers. The rising exodus is a mark of success, Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said, and `` we welcome it.'' Most Jews who leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have permits to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. But the vast majority opt for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> once they reach <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was receiving 10,000 applications a month from Soviet Jews for admission into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Another 10,000 a month were applying through the Dutch Embassy for emigration to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he said. `` The rate is going straight up,'' he said. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is pondering how to handle the situation, with a decision expected within a week or two. `` The administration is definitely not proposing to bar Soviet Jews from emigrating to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. `` We are not propsoing rules to make any Soviet Jews ineligible.'' Known to be under consideration is the addition of dozens of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> workers to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to handle the applications. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also is considering a six-month waiiting period for Soviet Jews who do not have close relatives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We are seeking ways to fairly and equitably respond to the explosion in demand because of our successful efforts in pressing the Soviets to open emigration, `` Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. She estimated that applications will be received from up to 100,000 Soviet nationals in the fiscal year that ends Sept. 30. `` In fiscal year 1990,'' she said, `` we expect that the number of Soviet applicants could increase to around a quarter of a million.''
