<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSupply     09-07 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Supply,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Shipments Dry Up in Wake of Colombia Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Martinez, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The flood of drugs into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has dried up since <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s latest round of violence began, raising the price of cocaine and shrinking the size of crack rocks, authorities said Thursday. But they warn the sudden drop in trafficking may be temporary, and could simply be the work of middlemen trying to drive up the price. The Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Seventh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which has accounted for 97 percent of the more than 10,000 pounds of cocaine intercepted by the entire service this year, has seen import activity suddenly grind to a halt, said Lt. Cmdr <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Karonis </PERSON>. `` We're still carrying out the same operations as we were, but the boats are n't coming out, and the air drops are n't happening _ the targets just are n't there.'' <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, outgoing head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, said agents from his district, by far the busiest in the nation, had been tracking three to five air drops a week prior to the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> crackdown. `` That has now come to a standstill,'' he said. `` There was only one right after the violence started, and we were n't even able to confirm that.'' The only recent major cocaine haul _ 800 pounds on a freighter in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> on Saturday _ had been loaded and shipped before the violence began. Undercover agents trying to make cocaine buys have been put off for two to three weeks, and even though that period is about up, there are still no shipments ready, he said. The summer months have traditionally been the traffickers' busiest. In addition, money-laundering activity tracked by Customs is sputtering _ traffickers are still moving wire transfers for old cocaine shipments, but there are few new payments. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has also spotted the change, but agents there are n't sure if it marks a true disruption. `` Yes, there appears to be a slowdown of drug activity out of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a fluctuation in distribution, and a rise in the wholesale price of cocaine,'' said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON>. `` But we do n't know if that's because of what's happening in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, or if entrepreneurs are trying to take advantage of what's happening to raise the price.'' <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said the price of large cocaine shipments in the last two weeks has increased from $ 11,000 - $ 15,000 a kilogram to $ 18,000 - $ 19,000, with individual kilogram sales reaching as high as $ The scarcity is being felt on the street as well, says <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> police Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothlein </PERSON>, head of the county narcotics bureau. Street prices for a kilogram of cocaine have shot up about $ 7,000, he said. `` Crack, on the other hand continues to sell for $ 10 dollar a rock _ but some of the rocks are getting smaller,'' said <PERSON> Rothlein </PERSON>. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> attributes the disruption in part to the confiscation of planes used to carry cocaine from processing plants in southern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to coastal staging areas. The heads of the cartels are also having difficulties trying to control their operations while on the run, he said. But how long the situation lasts depends on whether the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government can keep up the pressure. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> warns that the cocaine business is cyclical, just like any other commodity operation. `` There have been slowdowns before,'' he said. `` Slowdowns at different intervals ... are normal for the narcotics-trafficking business.'' He said other traffickers wait in the wings to replace anyone arrested or extradited, and planes and boats can be bought again quickly when the pressure is off.
</TEXT>
