<HEAD>Star Co. Studies Whether to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it has begun a study to determine whether the morning and evening newspapers should be merged. Publisher <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said in a letter to employees Thursday that no decision has been reached and no deadline set for deciding whether to merge the The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> with The <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. The study began several weeks ago. `` For years there have been consistent rumors that publication of the afternoon paper would cease,'' the notice said. `` These rumors have been unsettling to our employees, readers and advertisers. The time has come to provide a definitive answer.'' The Star publishes weekday afternoons and Sunday morning. The Times publishes Monday through Saturday morning. The Star reported Thursday that some employees speculated after the letter was posted that the study would concern itself with ways to accomplish a merger rather than to determine the viability of The Star. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said that speculation was false. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, who became publisher in 1977 shortly after the company was acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said one of the first questions he was asked was how long <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> would continue to publish the afternoon newspaper. He said Thursday that he did not have the answer then and does not have the answer now. The study will determine that, he said. `` I always said I did n't want to be here when that happened,'' <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. `` Nobody wants to preside over the death of a great newspaper, especially me.'' According to the 1989 edition of the Editor & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Publisher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yearbook </ORGANIZATION>, the Times has a daily circulation of 281,886. The Star's circulation was listed at 184,882 daily and 408,916 on Sundays.
