<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An abortion-rights coalition of women's groups and religious, labor, business and advocacy organizations on Thursday announced plans for rallies in the nation's capital and in cities across the country this fall to kick off a nationwide political organizing effort. Under the banner `` Mobilize for Women's Lives,'' the groups said they will use the Nov. 12 rallies and other events in the states to register supporters to vote, to enlist their help in political organizing and to boost the campaigns of abortion-rights candidates. `` We will make it the political issue of 1989, 1990, 1992, and we will change the legislative halls of this country so that we have pro-choice legislators everywhere in the majority,'' said <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>. Organizers said the coalition was formed before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s July 3 decision giving states broad powers to regulate abortions. NOW had wanted to stage a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> rally this fall to protest the court ruling, but other groups wanted more state and community involvement in the demonstration. Abortion-rights groups brought hundreds of thousands of people to the nation's capital in April for one of the largest marches in recent years in the capital and the largest abortion-rights demonstration ever. Police estimated the crowd at 300,000; organizers said their numbers reached 600,000. Coalition leaders declined to estimate how many people they believe will participate in the Nov. 12 events, but <PERSON> Yard </PERSON> said she expected it would be in the millions. Organizers said the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> rally is intended to demonstrate the unity and strength of the movement, while the events in the states will be designed to recruit vol