<HEAD>Measles Up Dramatically This Year After Two Year Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 10,000 measles cases were reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the first eight months of this year _ three times the number reported all last year. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> blamed the 1989 increase, which follows two years of declines, on the failure to vaccinate young children and ineffective vaccinations. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that 10,115 cases of the once-widespread childhood disease had been reported through last week. That's nearly five times the 2,170 cases reported at the same time last year and also is well above the 3,411 reported for the entire year in 1988. This year has seen a large number of outbreaks, most of them in the nation's high schools and colleges, the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. So far this year, more than 90 measles outbreaks have been reported, including one large outbreak among unvaccinated preschoolers in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, which struck more than 1,700. The unvaccinated young children, particularly in outbreak-prone inner cities, are one of two major impediments to wiping out measles in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. The other is the failure of vaccinations to protect some people, which has allowed outbreaks in `` highly vaccinated'' school populations. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year recommended a second dose of measles vaccine for children beginning kindergarten or first grade. Everyone born since 1957 _ when measles was so widespread that Americans had some natural immunity _ is considered a potential measles risk. `` It would be an expensive, exhaustive undertaking to revaccinate everybody born since 1957,'' but revaccinating children upon school entry should `` start chipping away'' at the problem, said Dr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wassilak </PERSON>, a CDC immunization specialist. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> also has recommended earlier vaccinations for inner-city children _ as early as 9 months, rather than the standard 15 months _ to try to prevent large outbreaks, and revaccinations for certain children in the case of school measles outbreaks. Specifically, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> recommended outbreak revaccinations for students who were vaccinated before 1980 or vaccinated between the ages of 12-14 months. In both cases, the agency said, studies have shown diminished vaccine effectiveness. `` The two-dose schedule and intensive efforts to raise ... immunization levels should facilitate the goal of measles elimination in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. But <PERSON> Wassilak </PERSON> cautioned that measles rises and falls in cycles, to some degree, and `` even if next year is low, that's not inconsistent. There's not going to be an immediate effect; it's going to take a while for the new policy to deter a significant number of measles cases. Federal health officials believed measles eradication was within reach early in this decade, when only a few remaining clusters of the disease remained. However, measles reporting then increased between 1983 and 1986. The 1989 total is already the highest since 1980, when 13,430 cases were reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The disease fell to a record low of 1,497 cases in 1983, but increased in 1984,'85 and'86, before beginning another decline, from 6,282 cases in 1986 to 3,652 in 1987 to the 3,411 in 1988. All this, however, pales in comparison to the prevaccine levels; more than half a million cases a year were routinely reported in the 1950s. A measles vaccine became available in the early 1960s.
</TEXT>
