<HEAD>Bill Allows Federal Agencies to Repay Some Student Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the hope of luring talented young professionals into public service, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel approved a bill Thursday to allow federal agencies to repay outstanding student loans of some employees. On a voice vote, a subcommittee sent to the full <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> the legislation, which authorizes a federal agency to repay up to $ 6,000 of an employee's federal student loan debt in any calender year. The measure also would give agencies the flexibility to pay or reimburse employees for degree training in certain occupations. The Subcommittee on <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> also passed on a voice vote a bill to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies from stacking performance review boards with political appointees. It merely clarifies sections of the Civil Service Reform Act by requiring agencies to have a majority of career appointees on review boards when making performance award recommendations. The subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON>, D-Minn., said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s present policy `` not only circumvents the spirit of the Civil Service Reform Act, but also undermines the very goal of a performance award system `` Instead of instituting a system which motivates and awards individuals for successful performance, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s policy threatens to politicize and void the award process,'' he said. The full committee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>., introduced the student loan bill Subcommittee members passed the measure with little fanfare or discussion because <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON> offered an amendment that addressed most of the problems raised by the administration during a July hearing. Under the amended bill, an agency may repay a total of $ 40,000 of an employee's student loan indebtedness. Employees can not be reimbursed for any loan payments made before the job began and must agree in writing, before receiving the benefit, to remain at the agency for a specified period, not less than three years. In selecting workers for the program, an agency is required in the bill to follow `` merit principles taking into consideration the need to maintain a balanced workforce representative of the racial, female-to-male ratio and ethnic makeup of our society.''
