<FIRST>u w AM-AcidRain     09-07 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Acid Rain,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine States Want All to Share Cleanup Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers representing nine states demanded Thursday that the entire country share the cost of cleaning up their states' acid rain emissions, but colleagues said states that foul the air should foot the bill. `` The country owes some help to those asked to do more,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, D-Ind., who is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> energy and power subcommittee and represents one of the coal-producing states that contribute to acid rain `` We are talking about economic justice for the country,'' <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said at a hearing of the subcommittee. The regional conflict, which has been festering for years, erupted anew with added urgency because President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and lawmakers from both parties are pushing for a new clean air bill. The question of who pays to clean up acid rain that is fouling lakes and killing trees would have to be resolved before such a bill is passed. Lawmakers from the nine states say their electric utilities produce 50 percent of the nation's acid rain pollution, but would have to finance some 67 percent of the cleanup under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan and other bills. The extra cost would likely be passed on to consumer and business electric bills in those states. That idea is vigorously opposed by miners who produce high-sulfur coal that is burned exensively in the nine states: <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> told the hearing up to 30,000 miners could be thrown out of work by the year 2000 unless other regions share the costs. Utilities would simply adopt the cheapest solution, he said, and switch to other fuels rather than installing expensive pollution-reducing equipment. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said it `` galls us'' that the nine states would pay `` more than our fair share.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moorhead </PERSON>, R-Calif., said other states have already paid to clean up their air `` The other 41 states have cleaned up their act'' and customers are financing anti-pollution efforts with higher utility bills. `` The nine states have the cheapest rates,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has had to do away with all our coal-fired plants'' and adopted technology that includes expensive solar energy and wind machines, he said, asking why the 41 states `` should pay for states that have not cleaned up their act.'' Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., argued that states such as <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> `` went to the expense, they went to the trouble Now you're saying we should bear part of the cost. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan calls for reducing sulfur dioxide emissions by five million tons by 1995 and by 10 million tons by 2000. The cleanup burden in the first phase would fall entirely on 107 utilities burning high-sulfur coal in 20 states. But after 1995, utilities that exceed their cleanup requirements could trade credits with other utilities and with other industries. Sulfur dioxide, and nitrogen oxide _ which has its own reduction schedule _ are the main components that form an acid in the atmosphere and destroy trees and lakes thousands of miles from the emissions. Refineries and smelting plants emit these pollutants also, although certain coal-burning utilities are the main culprits.
</TEXT>
