<HEAD>Medfly Quarantine in Effect, Spraying Begins Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture officials plan to begin an air attack on the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> fruit fly Friday night, seven years after similar sprayings in the area wiped out an invasion of the voracious insects. Only 16 medflies have been found so far, but those were enough for federal and state officials Thursday to seek a quarantine of fruit from a 60-square-mile area in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The quarantine from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> is voluntary until the filing becomes official next week. Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> declared a state of emergency Wednesday, letting authorities spray the pesticide malathion without issuing an environmental impact report that could take months to prepare. At 9 p.m. Friday, if the weather is good, two helicopters are scheduled to begin five hours of aerial spraying in a $ 2 million battle against a bug that is capable of causing up to $ 50 million damage locally to tomatoes, apples, pears, grapes and other produce. Millions of sterile medflies will be released in 10 days in a further attempt to stop the spread of the pests. In 1980-82, the state sprayed 1,400 square miles in eight counties to wipe out a medfly infestation. That war cost $ 100 million to fight and cost <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> growers another $ 100 million in lost sales. Medflies started showing up in traps Monday, and state officials Wednesday completed a ground spraying of malathion on a 200-square-yard area around a peach tree where the larvae were breeding. Agriculture officials, who are checking 1,700 traps in an 81-square-mile area, warned residents to cover their cars and remain indoors during the aerial spraying on trees and lawns. The quarantine, the officials said, is necessary to prevent widespread infestation. `` It has to be emphasized that the reason the quarantine kept expanding last time is people kept ignoring our warnings about moving fruit out of that zone,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wassenhove </PERSON>, the county agricultural commissioner. Statewide agriculture is a $ 16 billion per year industry. Last year, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s agricultural production was worth $ 142.5 million, with $ 94.3 million of the total in fruits, nuts, vegetables and nursery crops that are among the 250 crops that the medfly devours. <PERSON> Gera </PERSON> <PERSON> Curry </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, said harvesters, truckers, processors and sales people also would be hurt by a medfly infestation because every $ 1 in agricultural sales produces $ 3 in the general economy.
