<HEAD>House Panel Approves Child Care Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday approved its own version of a bill to help low-income parents with their child care costs, providing the bulk of the aid by raising existing tax credits and entitlements. On a voice vote, the tax-writing panel rejected a competing version by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that would establish a new program of direct child care subsidies to middle-as well as low-income families. With the legislation a key priority for members of both parties, the chief <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> sponsors of the competing versions said they hoped to reach a compromise and avoid a politically damaging fight on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. `` We're not that far apart; we want to avoid Democrats fighting Democrats,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chief author of the Ways and Means version that, because of its reliance primarily on tax credits, is more agreeable to Republicans and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. With the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> having approved a shotgun marriage of the two approaches in June, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., has said he hopes to bring the legislation to the floor for a vote before the end of September The Ways and Means panel's voice vote Thursday was a virtual repeat of the same stand in took in July. However, the committee amended its proposal to begin raising the existing child care subsidies that the federal government finances through block entitlement grants to states by $ 200 million in 1990 rather than in 1991. Those entitlements _ meaning the money does not have to be appropriated for them every year _ are designated for a wide variety of programs to aid the poor and are now capped at $ 2.7 billion a year. No one knows exactly how much of that existing entitlement money is actually spent on subsidizing child care, but estimates range from $ 400 million up to slightly over $ 1 billion. Whatever the total is, the legislation envisions increasing the amount devoted to child care by $ 400 million a year by 1994. All versions of the legislation envision increasing direct federal child care subsidies by a total of $ 1.75 billion over the next five years. Included in the total are increases in the existing Head Start program for poor children ages 3 to 5 and so-called `` latch-key'' subsidies for keeping elementary schools open as care facilities after classes have ended for the day. Indirect aid through an increase in the earned income tax credit for low-income families would total some $ 11 billion under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill and $ 13.5 billion in the House Ways and Means version. That credit, which is indexed to inflation, now totals a maximum of $ 910 a year for a family with an income of between $ 6,500 and $ 10,240. For every dollar of income above the $ 10,240, the credit is reduced by a dime, reducing it to zero for a family with an income of $ 19,340. The income threshholds for elibility also are raised every year by the rate of consumer price inflation. In 1991, the first year that the new child care tax credit would take effect, the maximum _ instead of the projected $ 1,002 _ would rise to $ 1,217 for families with one child under the House Ways and Means version. It would rise to a maximum $ 1,504 a year for families with two children and $ 1,790 with families of three or more children.
