<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday rejected an appeal by <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>, the farm labor contractor convicted of murdering 25 farm workers in 1971. The justices unanimously denied a hearing on <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s challenge to a lower-court ruling upholding his convictions. He was sentenced to 25 years to life for each of the murders. The bodies, most of them stabbed or hacked to death, were found in shallow graves in orchards in the <LOCATION> Marysville-Yuba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area. Defense lawyers denied <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s guilt and blamed the murders on a half-brother, now dead. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s first convictions were overturned on appeal because of a finding that his lawyer had acted incompetently and had a conflict of interest. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> was convicted again at a second trial. The 1st District Court of Appeal upheld the convictions in June despite finding that a reported confession by <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> had been admitted into evidence improperly. A Mexican consul, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>, testified at the second trial that <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> had told him in 1978 he had killed the farm workers because he was a `` sick man.'' Under an international agreement, consular officials can not be required to testify about matters related to their official duties unless their government issues a written waiver. The Mexican government did not try to stop <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> from testifying but did not furnish a written waiver. The appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> Colusa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, who presided over the retrial, should have excluded <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>'s testimony and was wrong in deciding that the consul was authorized to waive the privilege of confidentiality on his own. But the court, in an opinion by Justice <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s rights were not violated because the right of confidentiality was held legally by the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government, not <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>. As a result, <PERSON> King </PERSON> said, the defense can not complain that violation of that right deprived <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> of a fair trial. `` We are fully satisfied that <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s second trial was fair and that, ultimately, justice has been accomplished for both <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> and the people of this state,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. In seeking state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>, said Hispanics were not represented adequately on the grand jury that indicted <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mendelsohn </PERSON> challenged the appeals court's conclusion that <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> was required to show that the lack of Hispanics had harmed his case.
