<HEAD>Hamilton Urges Ongoing Iran-Contra Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee that investigated the Iran-Contra scandal said Thursday that so many questions remain about the role of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and others that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should not yet close the books on the affair. Rep. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, D-Ind., asked that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> begin `` a continuing investigation'' of new documents and other evidence that have surfaced in the trial of former Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> or which may surface during other upcoming trials of Iran-Contra figures Congressional investigators in late 1987 concluded that top <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials had circumvented the law to sell arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and generate money to buy weapons for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels But the yearlong probe failed to fully pinpoint the extent of personal responsibility of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and others. `` Most importantly, we still do not understand precisely what were the roles in these events of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other top <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman Rep. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beilenson </PERSON>, D-Calif. `` Congress was charged with the responsibility to investigate these events thoroughly and to understand them as best we could We will have failed to discharge fully that responsibility if we leave important evidence unexplored,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> wrote. `` In light of the importance of the questions that remain and the enormous implications of the events that have occurred, I do not believe we can consider the congressional investigation of the Iran-Contra affair to be complete.'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> acknowledged that there is a certain weariness with the matter on Capitol Hill, but noted that each new effort to dig back into the affair has shed new light. He asked that as part of its continuing probe, the Intelligence panel ask the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> White House to undertake a comprehensive search of all relevant <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration files, including the `` heads of state'' file recently discovered at the Reagan Library in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` It is possible that other important documents were missed by have not yet come to light,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> wrote. He also asked that the committee evaluate the seven new documents turned up at the North trial, which strongly suggested a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration deal with the Honduran government under which the Hondurans would help the Contras in return for increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid.
