<HEAD>Bush Asks Congress for First Installment in Aid to Hungary and Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday for the downpayment on a $ 150 million aid package for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said it might increase the amount if more economic and political reforms are adopted by those countries. For the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> requested $ 33.5 million. `` We'll always be looking for opportunties to increase that aid but we believe certain economic reforms and political reforms are necessary as a link with any real increases in aid, so we have some assurances that it is, indeed, revitalizing the Polish economy,'' said White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote to congressional leaders and asked for rapid approval of his request. In addition to the economic aid, the administration is preparing a $ 58 million package of food aid for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> that is expected to be ready around Oct. 1. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` We want to get all the food aid in there we can.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced the $ 150 million package during his July trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have urged the administration to expand the package to reward the installation of Solidarity member <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> as prime minister of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. The president discussed the package, along with other subjects, with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> during a meeting at the White House. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., who earlier had recommended a higher figure, said, `` I think he's doing what he should do in providing the leadership, working with the Western alliance. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said `` the bottom line is ... it's primarily the responsibility of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, said he recommended to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that he name a task force of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessmen, labor leaders and others to work with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s government to identify the reforms it should adopt `` to get from a communist economic base to a more productive base.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the idea is being considered. In July, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would provide <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> with $ 100 million to spur private enterprise and $ 15 million for environmental projects. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is to receive $ 25 million for entrepreneurial projects and $ 5 million for environmental projects. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also requested $ 5 million to promote organized labor.
