<FIRST>r w AM-CommonCause-FEC     09-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Common Cause-FEC,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Accuses Election Watchdog of Willful Inaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Common Cause accused the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Thursday of falling down on its job of policing federal campaign finance laws, claiming the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` seemingly willful refusal to act'' has encouraged illegal practices. The self-styled citizens lobby said the problems are so pervasive `` the best, albeit drastic, remedy may be to abolish the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> altogether and to create a new election law enforcement agency.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> in recent years increasingly has abdicated its most basic responsibility _ to enforce the law,'' Common Cause said in a report. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Eiland </PERSON>, a spokesman for the election commission, said he was n't certain whether the agency would issue a response. Common Cause is an enduring critic of the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> and has sued the agency frequently. The failure to enforce the federal campaign finance laws `` springs both from the structural defects <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> created in the agency and from the recalcitrance of the commissioners themselves,'' the study said. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> virtually has ignored the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to enforce the law.'' Under laws passed after the Watergate scandals in the early 1970s, the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> is charged with administering public funding of presidential campaigns, policing public disclosure, interpreting laws pertaining to presidential and congressional elections, investigating alleged violations and undertaking enforcement actions. Common Cause spotlighted so-called `` soft money'' practices in which contributions from corporations, labor unions and invididuals are channeled to state and political party organizations. The study said that in 1988 the presidential campaigns of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` together raised up to $ 50 million in soft money contributions from corporations, labor unions and individuals in donations as large as $ 100,000, money that is strictly prohibited in federal elections campaigns.'' `` Although this occurred in full public view, the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> took no action to stop it, in spite of a federal court decision ordering the agency to issue new soft money rules.'' The study said, `` by its inaction, the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> virtually issued an invitation to presidential campaigns to continue violating the law, an invitation which both presidential campaigns seized upon.'' Common Cause said such inaction discourages voluntary compliance with the law, encourages non-compliance `` to the point where the integrity of the presidential campaign finance system, in particular is now at risk.'' The advocacy group praised the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> for performing well in the areas of public disclosure of campaign records and administering the distributions of public funds.
</TEXT>
