<FIRST>u w AM-StarWars-Quayle     09-07 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Wars-Quayle,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Quayle In Step On SDI: Fitzwater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Thursday there was no difference of opinion between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on the Strategic Defense Initiative. The spokesman also said that former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had not exaggerated the potential ability of SDI to defend against incoming nuclear missiles. The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published an interview with <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on Thursday in which the vice president suggested that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had resorted to `` political jargon'' in his original, 1983 sales pitch for a multi-billion-dollar research effort aimed at creating a space-based defense shield. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in launching his SDI initiative, `` talked about this impenetrable shield that was going to be completely leak proof.'' `` I believe that in the semantics of let's say political jargon, that that was acceptable. But it clearly was stretching the capability of a strategic defense system,'' said the vice president. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s comments reflected `` the fact that we have been able to winnow the objectives of the program to ... fit more definable kinds of objectives.'' He said there was `` no difference'' between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on SDI. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was `` just saying there was some strange language associated with some of the discussion of it,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` But he believes in it.'' Referring to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s `` political jargon'' phrase, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> added, `` The only thing we have different today is two inflammatory words.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> still has not given up the goal of perfecting a space shield against all incoming nuclear missiles. `` That's kind of the goal that you keep working for,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. The `` ultimate goal,'' he added, remains `` a space shield that protects against the intercontinental ballistic missiles.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, an early, ardent advocate of SDI, said in the interview that the on-going research effort on SDI has been `` clearly rethought,'' with emphasis on an approach called `` Brilliant Pebbles'' that would rely on clusters of mini-missiles to track and knock out incoming rockets. `` We have redefined Star Wars and put it into missions, requirements, doctrine and strategy much differently than we did in the early 1980s,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the new emphasis could help protect the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against an accidental launch or a limited nuclear attack `` rather than an all-out, bolt-out-of-the-blue attack'' by the Soviets. The administration's request for $ 4.9 billion for SDI research for fiscal 1990 is under attack on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> wants to cut $ 1.8 billion from the program.
