<HEAD>Arabs Claim Graveyard Bulldozed to Improve View for Villas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli Arabs demanded an investigation Thursday of claims that a century-old Moslem graveyard was bulldozed so adjacent villas would have a better view of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. `` The municipality does nothing when a graveyard is criminally desecrated and the bones of the dead are crushed by bulldozers of people who have no morals,'' said a statement released by Moslem leaders who gathered at the site near <LOCATION> Herzliya </LOCATION>, a coastal town eight miles north of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. Moslem clerics and three <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> members of the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> parliament said the city sent the machines to change a pipe in the graveyard, then the workers hauled away hundreds of cubic yards of earth to give the villas a better view, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> reported. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio quoted Mayor <PERSON> Eli </PERSON> <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> as saying the bulldozers did not enter the graveyard, but that the city would investigate. It quoted him as saying the incident was an `` attempt to create friction between Arabs and Jews.'' <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> quoted <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Rafi </PERSON> <PERSON> Edri </PERSON>, who owns a house in the area, as saying no graves were violated. `` If there was any desecration of a graveyard, I'd be the first to scream,'' the independent paper quoted him as saying. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislator joined neighbors in helping pay for the earthmoving work.
