to Agriculture Commissioner Cleve Benedict.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents vote Saturday on three proposed changes to state government in a special election that could serve as a referendum on Gov. <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Capterton </PERSON>'s first eight months in office. <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>, a Democrat, could win broad, new powers if two of the measures pass. One amendment eliminates three statewide elected offices _ secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, treasurer and agriculture commissioner _ and places their duties under the governor's control. The second gives the governor control of the state primary and secondary education system, taking it away from the largely independent state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. The third gives cities and counties the ability to merge or choose new forms of government. Leading the campaign against the first amendment are two of the officeholders _ Secretary of State <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Hechler </PERSON>, a Democrat, and Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Cleve </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON>, a Republican. `` This is a much larger issue than party loyalty,'' <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON> said. `` This is a very fundamental choice on who we, <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Hechler </PERSON> and I, trust to exercise power _ whether we trust citizens at the ballot box, or whether we trust the political elite.'' <PERSON> Hechler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON>, both former congressmen, say they are n't campaigning just to save their jobs; the amendment would n't take effect until their terms end in 1992 `` I'm just a temporary occupant,'' said <PERSON> Hechler </PERSON>. `` It belongs to the people, and future generations ought to continue to have the right to choose whoever they want.'' The third official, Treasurer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Loehr </PERSON>, supports <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>'s plan <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Loehr </PERSON> to the post in July after two-term Treasurer <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> resigned rather than face trial in the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> over the loss of $ 279 million from an investment fund his office supervised. <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> contends he can save $ 3 million a year by assigning the officeholders' duties to other officials. `` This is not a turf war,'' <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> said in his weekly radio address last weekend. `` It's an economic battle.'' He said critics who accuse him of a power grab are distorting the issue. Saturday's election comes at a time of widespread trouble in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> politics. In addition to <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>'s resignation, Attorney General <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> resigned Aug. 21 to halt a grand jury investigation of his campaign financial records and allegations that he lied under oath. Former state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonkovich </PERSON> went on trial Thursday on federal extortion and racketeering charges. Three others, include the former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, pleaded guilty to lesser charges in exchange for their testimony for the government. Supporters and opponents say the special election for 868,802 registered voters could turn into a referendum on <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>'s first eight months in office. <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>, a millionaire businessman, won a landslide victory last November over <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> incumbent <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. One of his first acts was to push through the largest tax increase in state history, $ 392 million, despite a campaign promise not to raise taxes. `` There's a lot of anger out there about the tax increase, a lot of anger about politics of the past, about broken promises,'' <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON> said. `` Those are all probably going to be factors in the outcome.'' Former Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Underwood </PERSON>, who is supporting the amendments, agreed that <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>'s job performance will be a factor. `` Constitutional revision should never be a referendum on the incumbent,'' <PERSON> Underwood </PERSON> said. `` At the same time, it is almost impossible to keep that element out of the issue.'' A statewide survey conducted Aug. 19-23 for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> Daily Mail and <ORGANIZATION> WSAZ-TV </ORGANIZATION> showed that two-thirds of the registered voters surveyed knew little about the amendments, but a majority said they would vote against the two measures that would give the governor more power. The secretary of state's office maintains records regarding corporations and supervises state election laws. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> regulates farming and provides assistance to farmers and gardeners. The treasurer's office handles state investments and maintains the state's bank deposits. If voters approve the amendment, the remaining elected statewide jobs will be governor, attorney general and auditor.
