<HEAD>Navy Says Suicidal Behavior All But Impossible to Guard Against</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iowa Inquiry Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> admirals said Thursday it would be virtually impossible to guard against the type of suicidal behavior they believe caused the explosion that killed 47 sailors aboard that USS Iowa last April 19. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> report said `` circumstantial evidence'' indicated Gunner's <PERSON> Mate </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>, who was closest to the breech in the middle gun of turret No 2, dropped a detonator between bags of gun powder being loaded during firing exercises off <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. `` As with any catastrophe, the immediate impulse is to take every possible step to prevent a recurrence,'' wrote Adm. <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> A.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trost </PERSON>, the chief of <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> and the top officer in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Trost </PERSON> said, `` it is virtually impossible to have established procedures to absolutely preclude disastrous results of such an individual choice.'' Documents released with the report show <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> was depressed over the collapse of a close friendship, and one letter from <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> 11 days before the explosion eulogized sailors who died in action and said, `` I could become one of those little white headstones in Arlington National Cemetery.'' The report said <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> `` was emotionally capable of committing suicide, probably with the intent of killing others also.'' The report used the words `` repugnant'' and `` incredulous'' to describe the idea that `` an intentional human act'' sparked the blast, but concluded that <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> was `` the principle suspect.'' `` We do n't know the motivation,'' said Adm. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Edney </PERSON>, the vice chief of naval operations. <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> press conference the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> did not plan to change its psychological screening procedures. `` We did n't see anything that required a drastic change,'' he said. <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>'s allegedly suicidal character only became apparent after interviews with his acquaintances and family over the course of the four-month investigation, <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> said. `` He was a clean-cut sailor. He did n't smoke. He did n't drink. He did n't carouse on leave. ... He was n't a troublemaker,'' said <PERSON> Edney </PERSON>. The investigation also uncovered lax procedures aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, the report said, and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> announced immediate steps to correct them. The circumstances of the explosion are muddied by `` a number of major administrative and supervisory discrepancies on board the USS Iowa, as well as substantial and serious failures by senior <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> personnel to properly discharge their responsibilities,'' Adm. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>, said in a letter released with the report. But, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> wrote, `` exhaustive testing and evaluation has virtually ruled out any of these discrepancies as directly causing the deaths of the 47 crewmembers in Turret 2.'' `` Nevertheless, the number and egregriousness o the discrepancies create an impression of laxity and disregard that will cloud the investigations in the minds of non-experts for the immediate future,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> wrote. Among the problems cited in the report were a failure to fully train sailors in the gun turret on firing procedures. To prevent a repeat, `` all battleship weapons departments are to be inspected and deficiencies corrected prior to authorizing full unrestricted use of 16-inch gun systems,'' the report said. Rear Adm. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>, who led the investigation, concluded after numerous tests none of the irregularities could have sparked the blast. He began to investigate the possbibility that the explosion was intentional after receiving a letter from <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubicina </PERSON>, saying <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> meant to change the beneficary of a $ 100,000 accident death insurance policy to his parents from another sailor aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kendall </PERSON> <PERSON> Truitt </PERSON>. <PERSON> Truitt </PERSON> was once a close personal friend of <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>, but the friendship had cooled after <PERSON> Truitt </PERSON> became involved with a woman, <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> said. Although <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> said he found no evidence that <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> was a homosexual, documents released with the report show investigators were examining possible `` homosexual activity'' and `` <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON>'s alleged homosexuality.
