<HEAD>Heat Warms South, Rain Heavy in Iowa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Summer warmth and humidity prevailed Thursday across the Gulf Coast states and from the <LOCATION> southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> to the Great Lakes, while heavy rains drenched parts of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Scattered showers and thundstorms hit <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, southeast <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, parts of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and coastal <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, as well as <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, eastern <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. There were also a few showers in the central Appalachians. In southwest <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, thunderstorms brought 5-6 inches of rain Thursday morning to parts of southern <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> and northern <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> counties. Some small streams overflowed in the area and streets were flooded in <LOCATION> Corning </LOCATION>. Wind gusts reached 44 mph around <LOCATION> Yankton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, as thunderstorms dumped heavy rain. Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included almost 2 inches at <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, and more than half an inch in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Spencer </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. A cold front extended from the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> area. Cool autumnlike weather settled into the northern <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION> and northern high Plains under a high pressure ridge that extended from western <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Sunshine prevailed Thursday afternoon from the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> to the <LO