<FIRST>r a AM-DivorceRates     09-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Divorce Rates,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Divorce Rates Higher When Wives Better Educated Than Husbands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Married couples are more likely to divorce if the woman has more education than her husband, a study concludes. The study found that the divorce rate for marriages in which the wife has more schooling than her husband is over 50 percent higher than it is for marriages in which the husband has the same or higher educational achievement. `` Apparently many men and women have not been socialized to accept the notion of a woman being educationally more accomplished than her husband,'' said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, an associate professor of sociology at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who led the study. That women are better able to support themselves and less fearful of going it alone, could account for the higher rate of divorce, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` We might have expected that couples who had very different levels of education, regardless of which spouse had the higher education, would have higher divorce rates than average because these couples would have different world views and be subject to greater conflict and stress in their marriage. `` But that was not true. We found only couples in which the wife was more educated than the husband had higher divorce rates than average,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in an interview Wednesday. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, about half of all marriages today will end in divorce. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s study has not been published, but the results were presented last month at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sociological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The study was based on data from nearly 3,500 married or divorced women under age 50, collected by the National Survey of Families and Households between March 1987 and May 1988. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> received widespread attention three years ago when he concluded that single, college-educated women over age 30 had only a 20 percent chance of getting married. A <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> researcher, studying the same statistics, disputed his findings, and said those same women actually have a 66 percent chance of eventually marrying. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has done a new study on the same subject with more recent data, but the results will not be made public until they are published in November. In looking at divorce rates, the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> researchers also examined the effects of religious differences on marriages. Not unexpectedly, they found that divorce rates are higher for couples in interfaith marriages. When a wife and husband have different religion, but both are not very religious, the divorce rate is not much different from the average, the study found. To study the effect of educational differences, the women and men were placed in four different educational categories: those with less than a high school education, those with a high school education, those with some college education and those with at least a college degree. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> emphasized that men and women who marry someone who has a substantially different education, religous belief or age are generally less traditional than those who marry people with similar characteristics, and may therefore have less conventional views about marriage to begin with. Such factors, however, can not be measured.
</TEXT>
