<HEAD>Black Judge Named to Brooklyn Racial Attack Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sevens whites accused of killing a black teen-ager in the mostly white <LOCATION> Bensonhurst </LOCATION> district will be tried before a black judge whose assignment bypassed the usual selection process, court officials said Thursday. Justice <PERSON> Thaddeus </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, 70, was selected by a panel of judges and court administrators last week because of his experience and his ability to handle cases receiving a lot of publicity, said <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosson </PERSON>, chief administrator of the state court system. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' race played no part in the selection, <PERSON> Crosson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> was named solely because of his judicial excellence, <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> Chief Judge <PERSON> Sol </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtler </PERSON>, who oversees court administration, told the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, which first reported the selection in its Thursday editions. The judge had no comment on his appointment or on the case, his clerk said. Lawyers for the young white men charged in the Aug. 23 attack greeted the announcement with mixed reactions. The attorney for the accused shooter said he might file a motion to block it. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> DePetris </PERSON>, who represents 18-year-old <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Fama </PERSON>, said he objected `` not because of the judge that was selected but because it may violate my client's rights.'' <PERSON> Fama </PERSON>, who is being held without bail in the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION>, has been charged with murder in the attack and is suspected of firing the shots that killed 16-year-old <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> and three of his friends had gone to the mostly white <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> neighborhood to look at a used car when they were set upon by a gang of some 30 bat-carrying whites, the police said. Seven young white men who allegedly took part in the attack have been arrested and the police say they expect to pick up other suspects. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Santangelo </PERSON>, the lawyer for 21-year-old <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stressler </PERSON>, labeled the selection `` indiscreet, insensitive and illegal.'' However, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronne </PERSON>, lawyer for 19-year-old <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>, praised the selection, as did <PERSON> Mathew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mari </PERSON>, the attorney for 18-year-old <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Curreri </PERSON>. `` I've known <PERSON> Thaddeus </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> for a number of years and have tried a number of cases before him. He is a good man and a good judge,'' <PERSON> Aronne </PERSON> said. `` He's tough and we need someone tough who calls it the way he sees it.'' Judges usually are selected at random or specialize in certain types of cases. But for trials expected to generate high interest or controversy, court officials frequently handpick whomever they believe most suited to handle the case, <PERSON> Crosson </PERSON> said.
