<SECOND>AM-Non-Aligned,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Aligned Summit Ends, Adopts Resolution to Free Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The non-aligned movement ended its ninth summit conference early Friday after adopting a resolution calling for the release of all hostages. The four-day conference of 102 nations was attended by about 50 heads of state and a dozen prime ministers. It was due to end Thursday, but delays brought on by wrangling between hard-liners and moderates kept the summit going until after 1 a.m. Friday. The session passed a final declaration and adopted 30 political and economic resolutions dealing with topics ranging from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> to terrorism and drugs trafficking. Many of them were compromise resolutions, reflecting the deep divisions among members. The `` international terrorism'' resolution was agreed upon by the meeting's political committee after tough bargaining. It said the heads of state and government `` resolutely demanded that all hostages and all kidnapped persons be immediately released ... irrespective of the perpetrators and the place of the crime.'' The resolution condemned all acts of terrorism perpetrated by individuals, states or groups of states and expressed the movement's determination to fight such acts `` with all possible legal means, both nationally and internationally. Yugoslav spokesman <PERSON> Goran </PERSON> <PERSON> Milic </PERSON> indicated in a meeting with reporters at midnight that the final session was delayed about 5 -LCB- hours by disputes. Pleas for pragmatism and cooperation with the industrialized world contrasted with strident attacks on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Several delegates denounced `` Zionism'' in their speeches, a topic that caused problems to the very end. Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> insisted that in addition to the final document's stressing the `` struggle against imperialism, colonialism, neo-colonialism, racism and apartheid,'' it should also condemn `` Zionism and its practices.'' Heated arguments with moderates followed, with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> drawing support from such hard-liners as <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. A compromise was reached on including the `` Zionism'' reference in one of the many political resolutions, sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, in a bid to gain international prestige, sought to get the summit to agree to hold its next summit there, but no agreement was reached, conference sources said. Delegates did agree, however, that <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> would be the site for a non-aligned foreign ministers' conference to be held in 1991 in preparation of the 10th non-aligned summit. Moderates have emerged as the big majority and resisted throughout the summit attempts by radical nations to introduce cold war rhetoric. Yugoslav President <PERSON> Janez </PERSON> <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> told the closing session, `` We have achieved a high degree of unity about what the future of our movement should be.''
</TEXT>
