<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 30-year-old woman who was raped, beaten, stabbed and left to die in a crawl space of her burning home used her blood to scrawl the attacker's name on a wall, and police Thursday arrested her next-door neighbor. The woman, described by police as `` very, very brave,'' also cut her way out of the burning house with the knife that stabbed her and scaled a six-foot wall to escape, police said. She was in fair condition Thursday after undergoing surgery at <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> to repair sliced tendons in her right wrist. `` She's alert and awake ... but still is very frightened because this person is still at large as far as I know,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Duchon </PERSON>, a hospital spokeswoman. <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, 18, who has lived next door to the victim for about two years, was arrested at a truck stop in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at 4:20 p.m. MDT, said <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police Sgt. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>. `` We got a teletype from the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police saying that <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> had told them he was wanted for rape, arson and attempted murder in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> Detective <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> said police in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> had gotten an anonymous phone call that <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> would be coming through the city trying to contact relatives. <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said extradition procedures would be started Friday. The woman's ordeal began Wednesday morning when she let <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> into her home to use a telephone, police said. She was robbed of jewelry and money and raped in the basement, <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said. She was beaten about the head with a hammer, stabbed in the arm and hand and left in the crawl space, which had been closed off with furniture. Her home then was set afire. The woman managed to write, `` <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON>, next door,'' in blood on the wall before she kicked her way out of the crawl space, <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said. She then used the foot-long knife that she had been stabbed with to break the basement window and then scaled a 6-foot fence in her backyard, screaming for help, police said. `` She is a very brave, gutsy woman,'' <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said Thursday after interviewing the victim in her hospital room. `` She at one point feigned unconsciousness and grabbed the knife from him.'' The residents in the middle-class northeast <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> neighborhood did n't know whether she was in trouble or looking for it. `` People did n't want to get involved,'' <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said. But one woman, who asked not to be identified, telephoned police after hearing the victim scream, `` Help me. Somebody help me.'' `` I looked out the window to make sure it was n't some kids playing around. I saw her climbing over the fence with a knife in her hand. I went and called the police,'' the neighbor said. `` She was disheveled, beat up, bloody, half-dressed. She looked crazy. Now that I've heard what happened, I guess I would be crazy, too,'' the neighbor said. After the incident, <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> left her business card in <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s front door and he called her later in the day He promised to go to police headquarters and answer questions, but never arrived, she said. He lives with an uncle, and <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said both the uncle and the victim's husband were shocked to learn that he was a suspect in the attack.
