<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:NeapolitanSound Adv15   09-07 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Neapolitan Sound, Adv 15,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Sept 15 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Classic Neapolitan Song Gets Rock 'n' Roll Revival</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORMIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pino </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> grew up steeped in traditional Neapolitan music, the sometimes mournful, sometimes joyous melodies passed down for centuries in this <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> city. But it did n't stop him from wanting to be <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON>. `` I loved rock' n' roll but I also loved my music, Neapolitan,'' says the 34-year-old singer. `` I am a big fan of <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>, and at the same time I'm a big fan of -LRB- Neapolitan crooner -RRB- <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Murolo </PERSON>.'' Today, <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> is leading a revival of the Neapolitan song, which made Italian music world-famous with such tunes as `` O Sole Mio,'' `` Funiculi, Funicula'' and `` Turna a Surriento'' -LRB- `` Return to Sorrento'' -RRB-. But instead of mandolins, it is electric guitars and a rock or jazz rhythm that mark the new Neapolitan sound. <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON>'s albums have won him huge audiences and encouraged a whole school of Neapolitan singers at a time when Italian performers account for less than half the record sales in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> while <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and British singers dominate the pop charts. `` Neapolitan song represents one of the main points of Italian culture. We members of the new generation said, ` let's create a fusion,''' explained <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> in an interview at his studio in <LOCATION> Formia </LOCATION>, 50 miles from <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>. `` That is, we fuse it -LRB- Neapolitan song -RRB- with modern music, a universal language, which could be jazz or rock or other kinds of music.'' With a faded T-shirt covering his husky frame, his gray-streaked black hair pulled back in a ponytail, there is no mistaking <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> for <PERSON> Enrico </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruso </PERSON>. But he does claim a number of other similarities with his Neapolitan predecessors. Like them, <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> sings about the sea, the sultry Mediterranean afternoons, the plight of the city's poor. He places special emphasis on melody, like past Neapolitans whose songs are still played in Italian restaurants the world over. And he uses the local dialect, which is laced with French and Spanish from <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>' colonial past and English from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers based in the area since World War II. In <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON>'s songs, the tradition is mixed with a rock or Afro-Cuban beat _ something that startled people when he first began playing it in the mid-1970s. `` It was something new, but it communicated emotion,'' said the musician. `` This is the important thing in the end.'' Indeed, crowds frequently join in an emotional chorus with <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON>, particularly for his older ballads such as `` Napule e'' -LRB- `` Naples Is'' -RRB- and `` <LOCATION> Terra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mia </LOCATION>'' -LRB- `` My Land'' -RRB- about the corruption and neglect that have scarred <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>. His success has helped fuel a boom in Neapolitan pop music, featuring singers <PERSON> Edoardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennato </PERSON>, <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Sio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>. A Neapolitan, <PERSON> Massimo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranieri </PERSON>, won the Italian national song contest `` <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Remo </LOCATION>'' last year with a new Neapolitan ballad, `` Perdere L'Amore'' -LRB- `` Losing Love'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON>'s songs aim to bring together not only Italian and American music, but the experience of the poor in the two countries. `` They're Neapolitan melodies but with the rhythm of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> blacks,'' explains <PERSON> Gianni </PERSON> <PERSON> Borgna </PERSON>, author of `` History of Italian Song.'' `` <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> suggests the poor of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> are a bit like American blacks, not so different from outcasts in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The modern tunes are a long way from traditional Neapolitan song, which was influenced by arias in <LOCATION> Donizetti </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Rossini </PERSON> operas, as well as French and Spanish traditions. <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> heard those songs while growing up as one of six children of a <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> port worker. As he taught himself to play the guitar in his teens, he also followed singers such as <PERSON> Peppino </PERSON> di Capri who were beginning to adapt Neapolitan melodies to a nightclub style. In recent years, <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> has increasingly worked with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Latin American musicians to experiment with other influences and establish broader appeal for his music. `` We are trying to develop this to get into the international market, which is very difficult,'' he said. `` If you do n't sing in English, you're out automatically.'' He hopes nonetheless to win broader success with a `` Mediterranean'' sound, featuring Neapolitan melody, Latin and blues rhythms and perhaps an English singer. While he is not an international superstar, his reputation has spread in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He has given concerts in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. In January, he will head for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for a concert series called `` Night of the Guitar,'' in which he will play instrumentals with guitarists including <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Robby </PERSON> <PERSON> Krieger </PERSON> of the Doors. <PERSON> Daniele </PERSON> says with the international contacts, his songs have developed a more modern sound. `` But they always have a reference to the Neapolitan way of communicating,'' he insisted. `` There's always that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Sept. 15</NOTE>
