<FIRST>s i BC-Peru-Note Adv10   09-07 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Peru-Note, Adv 10,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For use with BC-Peru-Cocaine War, b0586; and BC-Peru-Rebel Justice,
b0587.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 A 150-mile-long valley in central <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is the world's biggest producer of the coca leaf used in making cocaine and a main supplier of the drug cartels of neighboring <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, recently visited two key areas of the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huallaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> _ one, a government base from which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will soon be going to war against the cocaine trade at its source, an possibly against anti-government Maoist guerrillas; the other, a stronghold of the guerrillas who are cooperating with drug traffickers but also lay down tough laws of their own in the villages they control, including a ban on drug abuse. Here are his reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Sept. 10</NOTE>
