> Sununu </PERSON> for appearing at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s side so often. Still, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said, `` I can wander in to any meeting, any time. He -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- wants it that way.'' <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Eizenstat </PERSON>, a former senior aide to President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and now a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer and consultant, says <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> `` seems to have subdued his own personal agenda for the president's agenda, and seems to have achieved a sense of teamwork.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON>, a former aide in the <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which was rife with staff clashes, said <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> `` has exceeded expectations. There are still many tests out there. But, so far, people have to acknowledge that Gov. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> knows his way around more than people gave him credit for.'' While <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> made an early peace with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> -LRB- something <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> was unable to do -RRB- in an effort salve bitterness remaining from the 1988 presidential primaries, he has n't completely retired the hatchet he wielded for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during the presidential campaign. A favorite target has been Sen. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> which earlier this month dumped <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nomination of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> to head the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights `` Sen. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> is out there, to be blunt about it, trashing the president,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> says. But the chief of staff also has another role, one not often seen by the public _ that of White House jester. When <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stepped away from an Oval Office meeting briefly, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> impishly had a White House photographer snap a picture of the empty presidential chair as he and other top aides looked on intently. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> and national security adviser <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON> then presented an autographed enlargement to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. It was inscribed to `` President Skippy,'' from a staff `` who can see through you,'' a clear reference to cartoonist G.B. <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>'s long-running `` Doonesbury'' depiction of him as an invisible leader with a fictitious `` evil twin'' brother, Skippy `` It was in the middle of a tough week,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said. `` People feel comfortable doing something that breaks the tension a little bit. I think it allows for a decision to be made in a much more relaxed climate. And you usually end up with better decisions.'' Then there was the time he talked Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> into donning a gorilla suit to greet the president. Or when the staff turned the tables and all showed up at a meeting wearing black arm bands to mark <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s 50th birthday. The bespectacled, round-faced aide staff chief claims he's gotten a bad rap in the image department: that the perception of him as arrogant, imperious and aggressive is all wrong. `` What a lot of people miss was that ... I was governor in a state in which, constitutionally and statutorily, the governor's office was relatively weak. Running <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, he said, was in some ways much harder than running the White House staff. `` The pace down here is not as hectic,'' he said. What <PERSON> Sununu </PERS