<FIRST>s w BC-DrugsInAmerica Adv10-2Takes   09-07 1159</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs In America, Adv10 - 2 Takes,1178</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun AMs Sept. 10 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drugs in America: The Enemy Within</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This time, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can not simply come home. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> speaks determinedly of victory, but the fact remains, a generation after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is losing its second war. Again the carnage, the brutality and the futility radiate nightly into living rooms across the land. The scenes seem so familiar. The dead being carried off in body bags. Wives and mothers grieving over senseless loss. Bewildered children, ravaged by violence and disease. Commandos in flak jackets charging again and again into enemy havens, only to find them quickly reoccupied. This time, the homefolks are not seeing these things just on television. No matter how sickened, they can not demand that the politicians and the generals return their sons and daughters from some faraway combat zone. Because home is where the war is. Guerrillas are roaming the streets, not of <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>, but of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Not the jungles of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, but the farmlands of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, like every president of the modern era, has promised to win the drug war. It will happen, he said Tuesday, `` block by block, child by child.'' He has a new program, latest in a long line. In eight previous years, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, by his own account, was the hands-on administrator of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s drug war. Polls show most people believe that effort failed. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, crack cocaine has become `` the fast food of drugs'' and has spread from just three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities eight years ago to virtually every state, including rural areas, `` now manifesting itself in all strata of society.'' Not a happy legacy for the crime-fighting Reagan-Bush administration. Now, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would channel $ 261 million into <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> and other Andean nations to help finance the hunt for drug kingpins and their henchmen, for whom human life is cheaper than a coca leaf. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s drug users are spending an estimated $ 100 billion each year to keep them in business. To this day, some Americans affix exclusive blame to foreign villains, be they Colombian drug lords, corrupt Third-World generals or Jamaican immigrants. A recent poll suggests a majority of the public would favor the use of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to wipe out the drug exporting centers around the globe. Others argue that supply only exists to satisfy demand, and speak boldly of mandatory prison terms or hospital confinement for all drug abusers, as if there were room for them all. There is n't. According to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, 72 million Americans, or a whopping 37 percent of the population aged 12 or older, have used illegal drugs at least once in their lifetime. An estimated 14.5 million people had used them within a month of the federally sponsored <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> Survey on Drug Abuse last year. An estimated 21 million Americans have tried cocaine, at least 3 million are still occasional users and nearly a million are heavy users. About 28 million people used one banned drug or another, counting marijuana, in the last year. Drugs favor no race, sex or class. Three-fourths of illicit drug users are white; 41 percent are women, including 5 million of child-bearing age. The drug education council says 11 percent of all babies born over the last year were exposed to illicit drugs during their mother's pregnancy. Drugs are in the schools, the home and in the workplace. Eight percent of last year's high school seniors said they had used cocaine over the previous year; 10 percent of college students said they did so. The drug council says 3 percent of workers between the ages of 20 and 40 are cocaine users. In a recent survey, the nation's employers said as many as one in five workers have alcohol or illegal drug problems. Drug-related absenteeism, medical expenses and lost productivity are costing employers an estimated 3 percent of their payroll _ half the typical company's payment for an employee's Social Security coverage. There are some encouraging signs. The national survey on drug abuse has found a recent decline in so-called `` casual'' drug abuse by young people. Two years ago, an estimated 17 percent of college students were occasional users, compared to 10 percent today. But the number of heavy abusers _ particularly involving cocaine _ has risen sharply. The percentage of weekly and daily cocaine users has doubled since 1986; the number of cocaine-induced deaths recorded by hospital emergency rooms totaled 1,696 last year, up from 604 in 1984. Overall, emergency rooms treated 46,020 cocaine patients last year, compared to 8,831 in 1984, an increase of 421 percent. Like the brass-hat body counters in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, prosecutors and police often trumpet their battlefield victories to the news media _ seizures of vast quantities of drugs worth fortunes on the street, massive arrests purporting to destroy this or that trafficking ring. Like <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s tunnel light, such announcements bear little semblance to the real course of the war. Fact is, illicit drugs, especially cocaine, are in more plentiful supply, at cheaper prices, in more potent form, than ever. The marijuana smoked today is as much as 10 times more powerful than the stuff used by the flower child of the 1960s. A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> study shows the purty of cocaine sold on the streets increased from 29 percent to 73 percent in just the two years between 1982 and 1984, and has remained there. The price has dropped to under $ 100 per gram for the much purer, deadlier drug. Urban slums have long been the stomping grounds of drug dealers. But the arrival of crack, a potent and cheap derivative of cocaine, has done for those neighborhoods what gunpowder has done for <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Cocaine was once considered the rich man's drug. With crack rocks selling for a mere $ 5, nearly anyone, children included, can find a way to obtain it. Pharmacologists say the drug itself chemically induces more paranoia and violence than most any other, though another drug of choice _ PCP or `` angel dust,'' can be as bad or worse. And desperation among users, prepared to rob and kill for the money to buy it, and competition among sellers, eager to establish trafficking monopolies, heighten the explosive mix. The firepower and disregard for innocent life exhibited by the gangs of young punks marketing crack, from Jamaicans in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to the `` Crips'' and `` Bloods'' in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, is astonishing. `` Drive-by'' killings, the spontaneous murder of someone because he is dressed, sometimes unwittingly, in the colors of a rival gang, have become commonplace. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the cops who raided the arms cache of one drug gang found the usual assortment of machine guns and sawed-off shotguns along with, of all things, a cluster bomb. Cluster bombs, normally dropped from airplanes, are designed to kill anyone within a wide area.
</TEXT>
