<FIRST>s w BC-DrugsInAmerica Adv10-1stAdd   09-07 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs In America, Adv10 - 1st Add,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: wide area</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> recently sent its drug reseachers into schools located in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s poorer neighborhoods, where they interviewed adolescent boys in the ninth and 10th grades. The information was later corroborated by criminal activity reports and school records. Eighty percent denied using or selling drugs. But 28 percent admitted carrying a concealed weapon; 17 percent had participated in a group attack; 13 percent admitted selling drugs, making an average $ 1,000 per week; 11 percent had assaulted an adult; and 5 percent had shot, stabbed or killed someone. And that, from kids only 14 and 15 years old. Last month, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> study in 14 major cities found that more than half the men arrested for any serious crime _ and who volunteered for drug testing _ were drug users. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the figure was 82 percent. `` There should be no longer any question as to how much of a catalyst for crime the lust for illegal drugs has become in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today,'' Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. `` Drug users and traffickers will beat, rob and kill anyone for drugs and profits.'' The toll, of course, is not limited to physical violence. The House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control estimated in February that there are 6 million to 6.5 million Americans in need of drug-abuse treatment, including 1.3 million intravenous drug abusers. Currently, treatment programs are available for only 250,000 abusers, the committee said. Meanwhile, quite aside from the thousands of drug-stupified patients they treat, hospital emergency rooms are soaked with the blood of drug-related violence. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s homicide rate, 59.4 per 100,000 population, edged out <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s last year to make the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> the nation's murder capital. The majority of the killings were drug murders, and the rate is climbing again this year. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s police arrested 43,000 people last year. The vast majority were set free, mostly because the city had no place to imprison them. The same story applies in other cities. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, misdemeanor offenders are released on personal recognizance because there is no room in the <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jail. Nationwide, fewer than one in six people arrested on drug-trafficking charges spend more than a year in jail. <LOCATION> Rural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is hardly immune. In a survey of all 93 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> found cases involving major drug trafficking and related contract killings throughout the heartlands. `` We knew that the country was awash in narcotics and dangerous drugs, but we did not expect to find significant cocaine operations, for example, in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, or heroin trafficking in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>. `` Crack,'' he added, `` is everywhere.'' But cocaine is just the salt in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s drug stew. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s drug lords are not responsible for the 100,000 elementary school children who get drunk at least once a week on the beer and fruit-flavored wine coolers they see consumed by their parents and television heroes They are not responsible for the 48,000 youngsters who are killed or injured in automobile accidents caused by intoxicated drivers every year. They are not responsible for the five-fold increase in lung cancer since 1963 among women, who now smoke tobacco in nearly the same numbers as men. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> says half a billion workdays are lost each year because of alcoholism alone. That's a 2 percent loss in the nation's productivity. The federal government estimates that alcohol and drug abuse costs the economy nearly $ 200 billion a year. Two-thirds of that is attributed to alcohol. There is no end to this war. Alcoholics Anonymous and Narcotics Anonymous, the two most successful, self-supporting treatment programs, know there is no such thing as a cured addict; only a recovering one. Their members go about it one day at a time. The government can do no better.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun AMs Sept. 10</NOTE>
