<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv11   09-07 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 11,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Sept. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chicago Struggles to Cope With Measles Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 1,100 measles cases have been reported in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> as it copes with the worst outbreak in the resurgence of the disease this year. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said 1,123 measles cases were reported to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> health officials through Aug. 23, and that 78 percent have occurred in preschool children. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 9,650 measles cases have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, compared with 2,151 in the 1988 period. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> outbreak `` is similar to others among inner-city populations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in that it involves primarily unvaccinated black and Hispanic preschool-aged children,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Blacks and Hispanics account for 94 percent of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> cases. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> authorities have set up at least seven new vaccination clinics, which have administered at least 21,000 doses of measles vaccine. Door-to-door teams have given at least 2,000 more doses, and the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said vaccination clinics have also been set up in four hospital emergency departments. Measles, a once-common childhood disease, was believed on the verge of eradication in this country in the early'80s _ just 1,497 cases were reported in 1983 _ but case counts have increased since.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Federal Wildlife Officials to Split Whooping Crane Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal wildlife officials plan to split the world's only captive colony of whooping cranes this November to reduce the chance the flock could be wiped out by disease or natural disaster. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said 22 of the 54 endangered birds at the <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> would be shipped to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baraboo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION> `` The service has been concerned about having all of their eggs in one basket, literally,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Trauger </PERSON>, the center's deputy director. `` The service felt it was the prudent thing to do, to separate the breeding flocks, and there's enough breeders now to do that.'' The center started in 1987 to breed the rare birds under a joint program with Canadian wildlife officials. The <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> foundation was selected as the home of the new flock after considering several groups across the nation. Although the foundation has not bred whooping cranes, it has successfully bred 13 of the 14 other existing species of cranes in the world. Scientists hope that by successfully breeding whooping cranes in captivity, they will be able to establish another flock in the wild. An attempt to do that failed in 1975 when an experimental flock at the <ORGANIZATION> Grays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> failed to produce enough eggs to sustain the colony.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Apache Reservation Car Death Rate Seven Times Nation's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
