<HEAD>UAL Employee Buyout Would Have Advantages, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic under ESOPs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The biggest employee-owned company in the nation would be created if <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots and management succeed with their $ 6.75 billion bid for the parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> would lead a fast-growing group. In the past two years, more than 300 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have been acquired by their employees, according to <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blasi </PERSON>, a business professor and expert on employee ownership. Federal tax benefits and the wave of hostile buyouts have spurred employees to take over their companies completely or acquire big equity stakes. The latter category includes big corporations such as <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> would enjoy marked advantages over other employee-owned enterprises, some experts The company is widely recognized as one of the strongest and most profitable in the airline industry, giving it a head start under the new regime of employee owners. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, who is part of the takeover team, has said that under the proposal, the employees do not contemplate selling any essential assets or revising plans for expanding the airline fleet and routes. `` The fact that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> is in good shape certainly does give -LRB- employee ownership -RRB- a better start,'' <PERSON> Corey </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ownership </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. `` It's the first time it's been tried on this scale. If it succeeds, it would put in a whole new array of weapons for unions to use.'' That's a fairly big `` if.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, whose cooperation is considered critical, has expressed doubt that the takeover attempt could succeed because it would require enormous new debt. `` I look at it sort of pessimistically now, because we've done an analysis on <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> ... I think they've put a price on it that's too overpriced,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterpaul </PERSON>, general vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. `` We do n't see the future as rosy as a lot of people see it.'' That stance appeared to strengthen the chances that billionaire investor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> could succeed in his rival bid for <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>. If the pilot-management attempt does prevail, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> would displace car rental giant <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> as the nation's largest company owned by its employees. An employee stock ownership plan, or <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>, representing 11,000 <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> workers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> took the company private in a $ 1.75 billion buyout in September 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Vittoria </PERSON> says he received a letter over a year ago from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> pilots seeking his advice on ESOPs. `` I do n't think <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s size is a hindrance to an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Vittoria </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Asked whether its size could actually be an advantage for employee ownership, he replied, `` It could be, but it depends on management getting employees involved.'' <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> has a multi-tiered employee participation program that is considered a model by some experts. Worker representatives are elected by their co-workers and participate in monthly district-level meetings with managers to review operations and make suggestions. The local groups also elect representatives to attend quarterly zone meetings, semi-annual regional meetings and an annual company-wide meeting. Under the <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> pilot-management proposal, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> would own 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s stock for an investment of $ 750 million. The employees would agree to unspecified wage concessions in exchange for participation in an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> that would give them 75 percent of the company. News reports have indicated that the pilots union might invest as much as $ 1 billion. The rest of the buyout funding apparently would be borrowed. Only a small proportion, about 15 percent, of the employees participating in ESOPs are unionized. But the pilots, Machinists and flight attendants at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest airline, are strong unionists. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> under employee ownership `` would have to be run as a partnership, not as a feudal barony,'' said <PERSON> Blasi </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION>, whose book, `` Employee Ownership: Revolution or Ripoff?'' is critical of some ESOPs. `` In the airline industry, most ESOPs have not been combined with a strong employee involvement program. Board seats are not enough,'' he said. <PERSON> Blasi </PERSON> said he is waiting to see specific details from <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> and the pilots on how labor-management committees would be set up to address problems and make decisions. He cited a 1983-84 experiment with partial employee ownership at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, under former chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON>, which he called `` a great success.'' Under the program, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees generated ideas to improve productivity. An <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, before it was merged into <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, also was a good example of labor-management cooperation, <PERSON> Blasi </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, an aggressive regional carrier based in <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, is about 20 percent owned by its employees. And <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> established an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> in July, in a moved widely viewed as a deterrent to unwanted suitors as takeover speculation swept through the airline industry.
