<FIRST>r f PM-EconomicStatistics     09-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Statistics,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Government Failing to Track Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House budget office has been blamed for the inability of government statisticians to track significant changes in the economy and their effect on people and businesses, even while spending some $ 2 billion this year trying. While the skills of workers are increasingly recognized as key to economic growth and improving the nation's competitiveness, the government spends nearly seven times more collecting data on agriculture than education, said the congressional Office of Technology Assessment. `` It seems unlikely that this is the right ratio, given the transformation under way in the economy,'' the agency said Wednesday in a 40-page report. `` Even worse, no organization in either the executive branch or the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has assumed responsibility for asking whether it's the right ratio.'' The report, `` Statistical Needs for a Changing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Economy,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> was told in 1980 to set priorities and coordinate the government's statistics-collecting efforts `` While it has a mandate to perform this task,'' the technology experts said, `` <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> has not given it much priority and has dedicated few resources to the effort.'' Efforts by agencies in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and other departments to correct shortcomings have been hampered by White House budget officials, said the report, which was requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. As an example, it cited cuts in the budgets of most agencies for collecting and analyzing data during the past eight years and a resistance by <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> officials to allow new surveys sought by statisticians. `` These organizations are painfully aware of the problems,'' the researchers said. `` The greatest problem appears to be the absence of any central place in government where basic questions about priorities in statistics are being asked.'' Sen. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.M. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel's subcommittee on government information and regulation, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will likely have to force the issue when the 1980 Paperwork Reduction Act comes up for reauthorization next year <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the White House budget office, said its officials had not seen the report and so could not comment on it immediately. The congressional researchers acknowledged it has become much more difficult to develop meaningful statistics on economic growth and productivity with the emergence of an international market and a service-based <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. `` The most important inputs purchased by a business may be research and engineering information and the skills and education of its employees,'' it said. `` The existing statistical system makes it extremely difficult to anticipate the potential impact of emerging technologies.'' It cited computers and how changes in their capabilities and prices are reflected in the nation's economic growth, inflation and productivity figures. For example, it said, the price of one megabyte of computer memory capacity fell by 95 percent between 1972 and 1987. `` Measuring changes in the quality of computers, however, can seem easy in comparison with the challenge of measuring changes in the quality of services,'' the report said. `` How do you measure quality changes in legal services?'' Changes in the quality of health care and education, which together account for more than one-sixth of the nation's gross national product, are not measured at all, the report said.
</TEXT>
