<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Milken     09-07 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Allow Drexel To Pay Milkens; Firm To Enter Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After months of challenges and delays, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to plead guilty to securities crimes Monday and formally settle the highly publicized Wall Street corruption case. The court date was set after prosecutors switched course and allowed the investment firm to pay its former junk-bond chief, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, his 1988 compensation of more than $ 100 million, removing the last roadblock to the plea bargain. `` We are pleased that the government has reversed its position and dropped the unconstitutional provisions of its settlement with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Liman </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, said in a statement released Wednesday by a <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> spokesman. `` These unconstitutional provisions were a gross abuse of prosecutorial power,'' the statement said. `` Perhaps now the government will also reconsider its use and abuse in this case of the Draconian RICO statute.'' A 98-count indictment in March charged <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> with wide-ranging securities law and Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act violations. A broader indictment is expected next month. The hearing Monday before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kimba </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> should end months of negotiations and challenges over an agreement announced in January in the government's insider trading probe. The government's reversal to allow <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to pay its indicted former bond financier was made in court papers filed late last week. The move was first reported to be under consideration last month. Under the plea agreement, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> will enter guilty pleas to six securities and mail fraud felonies. The firm also has agreed to pay $ 650 million in fines and restitution. The pact had required <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to fire <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and withhold his compensation for last year, estimated in court papers at more than $ 100 million. The agreement also had barred <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> from giving <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> more than half his 1988 pay. Both <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> have since resigned from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. In a letter to <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> late Friday, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> said prosecutors dropped the pay provisions because of a bail agreement in which the government will monitor hundreds of millions of dollars of the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION>' assets. `` In light of this security, the matter of any payment to be made by <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> can be resolved adequately between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION>,'' the letter said. Lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> immediately dropped a motion filed in January challenging the plea agreement on the grounds that it unfairly denied the brothers their 1988 pay. Defense lawyers and other experts following the case have said they surmised the government dropped the provision withholding pay because of a belief it would be rejected in court as unconstitutional. Sources familiar with the case said the government acted independently. `` It was the government deciding on its own, 100 percent, that they wanted to drop it,'' said one source who asked not to be named. A separate settlement with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> of fraud and insider trading charges by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is to take effect once <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> enters its plea. Under that deal, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to broad structural changes and federal supervision for three years.
</TEXT>
