<FIRST>u f PM-WPPSSSettlement Bjt   09-07 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WPPSS Settlement, Bjt,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlements Approved in WPPSS Bondholder Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District judge says that plaintiffs in the nation's largest municipal-bond default might have gotten significantly smaller awards had they won their case at trial instead of settling. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, on Tuesday approved settlements to allow $ 750 million to be distributed to holders of <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> bonds in what he called `` one of the most complex lawsuits in the history of securities litigation.''. `` There is more than adequate reason to conclude that the aggregate amount of these settlements ... is fully satisfactory, given the risks associated with a full trial of the issues,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, trustee for the bondholders, in a statement quoting the judge's 106-page opinion, which was not immediately available. It was <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> who presided over the enormously complicated <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> litigation that in the last year resulted in settlements between <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and defendants in the case. The trial began a year ago in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> but defendants reached settlements by January. In April, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> held a fairness hearing on the settlement in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berls </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> vice president who has handled <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> matters, on Wednesday called <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>'s ruling a `` carte blanche'' approval of the negotiated settlements. `` This is a major milestone in the WPPSS litigation,'' he said. `` The bondholders are just one step away from distribution'' of the settlement money. The final step is for <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> to schedule a distribution hearing, at which attorneys will argue precisely how the funds should be distributed, <PERSON> Berls </PERSON> said. No such hearing has been scheduled, he said. In determining the distribution, the judge will emphasize when each bondholder purchased the bonds, <PERSON> Berls </PERSON> said. The plaintiffs in the case essentially broke down into two types of bondholders: those who purchased their bonds before the default on June 15, 1983, and those who bought bonds afterward. In 1983, <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> defaulted on $ 2.25 billion in bonds it had sold to finance construction of a nuclear power plant at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in Eastern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and another at <LOCATION> Satsop </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> had abandoned construction of those two plants in 1982 because of rising construction costs and doubts about the need for the plants' power. The default was triggered by a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that the participating utilities lacked the legal power to sign contracts with <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> guaranteeing payment even if no electricity was generated. Dozens of lawsuits were combined into one action against <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, all 88 utilities that contracted with the consortium to build the two reactors, engineering firms, Wall Street bond underwriters, utility and <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> directors and a consulting firm. The settlements approved require the defendants to pay $ 580 million into the Chemical Bank-administered settlement fund. Together with $ 107 million in settlements approved earlier, plus interest, the amount available for distribution in December would be $ 750 million, <PERSON> Berls </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Berls </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was not worried that <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> would have exercised his other option, that of rejecting the settlements. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>'s ruling `` validated all the actions we've taken,'' <PERSON> Berls </PERSON> said. `` I think the court by taking the action it did endorsed the end we were all trying to reach, which was peace,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> paid no money in the settlement in exchange for cooperation from its employees at the trial. Plaintiff's attorneys said there was n't enough money left in <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> to pursue. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> was building five nuclear reactors to generate electricity in the late 1970s, but only one was completed. Two remain `` mothballed'' for construction to resume if enough demand materializes for the electricity they would produce.
</TEXT>
