<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf pvs bgng: `For the ... ' to CORRECT year-to-date
sales to first eight, sted nine, months of the year; picks up last graf
pvs bgng: Domestic automakers ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 21.4 percent rise in late-August car and light truck sales may be a sign that sales will drop dramatically as the calendar year draws to a close, analysts say. The eight major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> based automakers reported Wednesday that their vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 49,276 during the Aug. 21-31 period this year, compared with a rate of 40,578 during the same time last year. `` We think a lot of the volume that we're seeing here is really coming out of the fourth quarter of this year or the first quarter of next year,'' said analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` The $ 64,000 question is really how bad is volume going to be in the fourth quarter,'' he said. With overseas makers' results added in, car and truck sales were up 8.4 percent in August over the same month last year. Car sales rose 11.2 percent and truck sales were 2.2 percent higher for the month. Typically, dealers offer closeout deals as the model year draws to a close, traditionally on Sept. 30. On top of that, manufacturers have been offering customers and dealers incentives that lower the prices of 1989 cars. Consumers also have been learning that prices for 1990 cars will rise, prompting some to buy now rather than later. `` Consumers have been bombarded by these price hikes on the 1990 models going up anywhere from 2 -LRB- percent -RRB- to 9 percent,'' said analyst <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> `` Domestic automakers have n't done that in a long time. `` It's people out there thinking ` I've got to buy a car by the end of the year.''' <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Adcox </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Adcox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said he has seen some increased traffic through his showroom recently, and incentives are the reason. `` With this factory incentive that they have given the dealers, it's going to lower the price of the car,'' he said. `` I just hope that it works. `` If it does n't you've got a lot of dealers who are not going to order'90 models. They ca n't have inventory on top of inventory.'' For the first eight months of this year, domestic and imported car and truck sales were running 3.7 percent behind the pace of last year, the second-best year in history. Car sales were down 4.1 percent and truck sales were off 2.7 percent. Domestic automakers held 77.3 percent of the car and truck market at the end of August, up from 76 percent at the same time last year.
