<HEAD>McDonald's Testing Fried Chicken in Houston, Dallas Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American consumer's continuing taste for chicken has prompted <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to begin eyeing the fried-chicken market. McDonald's has begun a new test at six restaurants in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and six in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, selling combination packets of two, three and nine pieces of deep-fried chicken. `` Americans are going toward lighter eating and we're following the tastes of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Horler </PERSON>, regional marketing manager for the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> region. The company already serves chicken in sandwiches, salads and in bite-size boneless bits. `` The testing is in the embryonic stage,'' said <PERSON> Horler </PERSON>. `` The question is, can we deliver a good quality, value-priced product in the quick environment we have?'' To find this out, the company is looking at how its equipment is handling the new product and what customers think about it. Sometimes, as with the company's experimental pizza, the product goes back to the kitchen for a recipe makeover after the operational testing and before it goes out for a full market test. McDonald's salads were in the testing phase for 10 years before being made generally available, <PERSON> Horler </PERSON> said. The fried chicken is being sold after 4 p.m., aimed at the family dinner business. There are three combinations: two pieces, a breast and leg, selling for $ 1.99; three pieces, breast, leg and thigh, for $ 2.89; and nine pieces, three breasts, three legs and three thighs for $ 7.89. Dinner rolls are included. The chicken is kept frozen and then fried for customers. No decision has been made on whether to expand the fried chicken experiment, <PERSON> Horler </PERSON> said.
