<HEAD>EEC Jobless Rate 9.3 Percent In July, Same as June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s average jobless rate was 9.3 percent in July, unchanged from the previous three months and 0.1 points below the rates of January and February, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> statistics agency <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday `` In the six months to July 1989, the unemployment rate for the Community as a whole has remained stable,'' <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` Falls in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> -LRB- -1.3 percent -RRB-, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdon </LOCATION> -LRB- -0.6 percent -RRB- and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> -LRB- -0.3 percent -RRB- have been offset by rises in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> -LRB- 0.6 percent -RRB- and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> -LRB- 0.3 percent -RRB- while the rates in all other member states have remained broadly unchanged.'' <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said the jobless rates have stabilized for both men and women at 7.3 and 12.2 percent respectively. It gave no figure for the total number of jobless in July, because of a new calculating method used in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. The figure for June was 14.1 million. <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> reported these unemployment rates for each <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> state at the end of July: <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, 9.7 percent; <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, 7.3 percent; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 5.8 percent; <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, 17 percent; <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, 10.1 percent; <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, 17.1 percent; <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 10.9 percent; <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, 2 percent; <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, 10 percent; <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, 5.6 percent and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, 6.7 percent.
