<HEAD>Protesters Claim Heinz Kills Dolphins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J.F </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> says his company and animal rights activists stand in agreement _ the slaughter of dolphins caught with yellowfin tuna must end. Aside from humanitarian reasons, <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> has a commercial interest in saving the dolphins because dolphins swim with tuna in the eastern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, leading fishing boats to their catch. `` We have more interest in the porpoise than they have ... if you see them as the sheepdog of the sea,'' <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said. `` The simple truth is that releasing dolphins represent a more successful fishing technique than ignoring their safety.'' <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> reacted after about 50 protesters, led by the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, picketed <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s annual shareholders meeting at a downtown hotel Wednesday, carrying anti-Heinz signs and chanting, `` <PERSON> Boycott </PERSON> tuna. <PERSON> Boycott </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>.'' Two protesters _ <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Heitchue </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> _ lowered themselves from a nearby eight-story building and unfurled a banner reading, `` Heinz Stop Killing Dolphins,'' before police arrested them on disorderly conduct, criminal trespass and criminal mischief charges. Another protest organizer, <PERSON> Candace </PERSON> <PERSON> Batycki </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, briefly disrupted the shareholders' meeting by screaming, `` You're slaughtering dolphins What kind of world do you want to live in?'' Protesters and company officials agreed thousands of dolphins are being killed with yellowfin tuna in large, encircling nets set mostly by foreign fishermen. Ms. <PERSON> Batycki </PERSON> estimated at least 150,000 dolphins die in the catch annually. `` It's not necessary to fish on dolphins, just easier,'' she said. `` They -LRB- <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> -RRB- have a lot of power in their hands. They have the power to end this.'' Protesters claimed a boycott of tuna products has hurt <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> StarKist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seafood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary and other producers <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> estimated <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> yellowfin tuna represents 20 percent of StarKist's catch But <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, in its first-quarter earnings report issued Tuesday, said StarKist's tuna contributed to a 15 percent increase in earnings. `` Our sales of tuna are at an all-time high,'' <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said. But he told shareholders the killing of dolphins was `` a legitimate concern.'' `` We're doing everything we can to save the porpoise,'' <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said. A new $ 100,000 research program, announced by StarKist last Thursday, promises to find ways of using sound to lure dolphins away or out of fishing nets, he said. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyth </PERSON> said the company is willing to spend more if early research is fruitful. None of about 3,000 <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> shareholders questioned <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> about the dolphins issue, but they applauded warmly at a review of <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s television commercials and when <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> announced a two-for-one stock split and a 16.7 percent increase in quarterly dividends On other matters, <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> will not accept irradiated food from suppliers and will not use radiation in any of its food processing. Sister <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> of the Sisters of St. Dominic of <LOCATION> Caldwell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, representing several <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> institutions holding <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> stock, said <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s policy follows a request by the Interfaith Center on Corporate Responsibility. She called <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s policy `` an unprecedented move by any <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. corporation.'' <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> also told reporters the company is trying to expand its food products into the `` gray market'' of senior citizens. He said <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> believes today's consumers will be more concerned with `` health and wellness'' as they age. He declined to speculate what products or companies the food conglomerate might produce or buy.
