<BYLINE>Pacific Lumber Heirs Sue Drexel Over Buyout</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three ex-heirs to the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have filed suit against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, charging fraud during the financing of a hostile buyout of the company. The suit filed Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Humboldt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Stanwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> received $ 40 a share for stock that was actually worth more than $ 70 a share. It seeks $ 18 million from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to cover the difference. The Murphys are descendants of <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who bought <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Humboldt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1905. It was bought by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. The suit also names as defendants former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> junk-bond king <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and former Wall Street financier <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who the suit claims secretly bought stock for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. The suit claims a scheme to take over the lumber company at a cheaper price was worked out in secret talks in the spring of 1985 between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and unnamed <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> officals. <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON> was not named as a defendant in the suit. According to the lawsuit, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> `` knew it would be able to sell these shares to <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION>, through <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, at a profit,'' but did not disclose its intentions. The suit contends that at the time <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> was attempting the takeover, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> filed a false affidavit indicating that it did not own any <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> stock. The suit contends <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> owned more than 5 percent of the redwood lumber company with <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> acting as its representative. Pacific Lumber's articles of incorporation required 80 percent shareholder approval of a merger deal if any stockholder owned more than 5 percent of the company. <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> held about 4.6 percent of the company's stock. Since <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> concealed its stake during the takeover attempt, shareholders assumed that the <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> bid needed only 51 percent shareholder approval, the suit contends. Many shareholders, believing they would be unable to stop a simple-majority approval, decided to sell to <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION>, the suit maintains. The suit says that concern that the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> affidavit was false surfaced in September of 1988 when the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filed charges against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> in a celebrated securities-fraud case. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to settle that case by pleading guilty to six felony fraud counts and paying a $ 650 million fine. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> is serving a federal prison sentence after pleading guilty to unrelated securities-law violations. Los Angeles-based <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, former head of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk-bond unit, has been charged with separate securities violations. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> officials could not be reached for comment.
