<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has nominated prominent <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> defense lawyer <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON> as successor to former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, the crime-busting prosecutor now running for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> mayor. <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON>'s nomination Wednesday, which had been widely anticipated, is expected to receive routine confirmation by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, though <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> once said he opposed the nomination because <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON>'s firm has represented targets of securities fraud investigations. `` I may be naive in that regard but I am more than happy to answer any of their questions,'' <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON> said in an interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after the nomination was announced. `` I've practiced law for 30 years and the great thing about being a litigator is we do all our professional work in public. The mistakes and the glories and the victories are all a matter of public record,'' he said. <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON>, 53, said he has none of the skeletons in the closet that have derailed some recent federal judicial nominations, as well as sitting politicians. `` I do n't think I buy outdated milk,'' he said. `` I do n't think I speed _ at least I do n't get caught at it. I pay my taxes. I'll even answer questions like, Have I ever used drugs? ... The answer is indeed no.'' <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, who resigned Jan. 31, has been temporarily succeeded by acting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON>, who said he would work with <PERSON> Obermaier </PERSON> for a smooth transition and then would return to private la