<HEAD>U.S.-Korea Telecommunications Talks Bog Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Talks on opening <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s closed telecommunications market to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> bogged down Thursday with both sides showing few signs of compromise, officials said. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> talks were called after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> named <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> as an unfair trader in telecommunications in February under the 1988 Trade Act calling for tough retaliatory trade sanctions. The meeting began Wednesday and continued until late Thursday night but there was little chances of agreement, said officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gordana </PERSON> <PERSON> Earp </PERSON>, the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate, asked <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to announce a timetable to open its market before July 1 next year but <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> officials refused to comply, saying their telecommunications industry needs two or three more years to grow, the ministry official said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> expressed willingness to accept parts of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s demands to open its market to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> telecommunications equipment but refused to allow direct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment in the market for value-added networks, the official said <PERSON> Earp </PERSON> strongly indicated that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> may impose trade sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> unless its demand was fully accepted, he said. The telecommunications talks were the first in a series of intensive trade negotations scheduled in the coming months between the two countries. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> officials are concerned that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION