<HEAD>Japanese Investment Increases in Britian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese businesses are `` more anxious than ever'' to gain a foothold in <LOCATION> Britian </LOCATION> before the European Community forms a single market in 1992, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials and businessmen said Thursday. `` The Japanese fear that after 1992, they will be locked out by a fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpe </PERSON>, director of investment in the government's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Industry-Northeast </LOCATION>. `` They are more anxious than ever to get into our area before 1992 to conform with our way of doing things. Our inquiry rate is greater than ever before,'' <PERSON> Sharpe </PERSON> said. The 12-member <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1992 will form the largest single market in the world, which will comprise more than 350 million people. `` The north of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> is the number one choice in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for Japanese investment,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> in the North of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> -LRB- NDC -RRB-. With 33 Japanese companies operating in the area _ the majority in the last few years _ a package that includes tax incentives, investment allowances and freedom from planning restrictions for Japanese manufacturers is being offered to attract still more. Government efforts are aimed at restoring investment and jobs in areas that have suffered economically from the decline of traditional industries such as shipbuilding and coal mining, <PERSON> Sharpe </PERSON> said. The government has alloated more than 150 million pounds, or about $ 231.5 million, over the next five years to transform the industrial structure of the area and will set up a special economic enterprise in <LOCATION> Sunderland </LOCATION>, where a <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> plant is located, to attract further Japanese investment, said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, director of business development for the Tyne and <ORGANIZATION> Wear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>. The northern region has operated a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> office since 1974, and its presence in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has been `` essential'' to efforts to attract Japanese investment, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> told a news conference. It sponsored a one-day seminar on business opportunities in the region attended by representatives of more than 200 Japanese companies. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NSK </ORGANIZATION> Bearings are the leading Japanese companies with plants in northern <LOCATION> Britian </LOCATION>. The Foreign Ministry recently opened an office to deal with Japanese companies' inquiries about trade barriers and regulations that will result from the unified market in 1992.
