<HEAD>Japan Orders Construction Firms To Stop Price-Fixing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Thursday it has ordered six Japanese construction firms working on a multibillion-dollar airport project in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to disband a price-fixing cartel. In a similar move, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has ordered 24 shipbuilders to end a production cartel by October, it was reported. The actions seem to indicate <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is responding to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> criticisms that price-fixing cartels prevent foreign firms from competing for business in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rill </PERSON>, assistant attorney general of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Setsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Umezawa </PERSON> in a meeting Wednesday that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should strictly enforce the anti-monopoly law, said the <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>, a major national newspaper. <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> participated in Japan-U.S. trade talks earlier in the week in which <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials said business practices such as collusion were preventing progress in shrinking the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Umezawa </PERSON> told <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> the <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> would take strong action against violators of laws prohibiting private monopolies and maintaining fair trade and said violators of those laws would be treated `` with a stern attitude,'' the paper reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, quoting reliable sources, said late Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> had ordered 24 top shipbuilders to disband a cartel formed to help them weather a serious slump in the industry. Japanese officials were not immediately available for comment late Thursday evening. The Fair Trade Commission's order to disband the construction cartel followed a year-long investigation into a price-fixing agreement among contractors supplying sand for the <ORGANIZATION> Kansai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, said a commission official. The Kansai airport became the focus of a major dispute between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> three years ago when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials claimed that corporate collusion and obscure bidding procedures were preventing foreign companies from winning contracts. Construction of the $ 6.7 billion airport off <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> began in January 1987, with completion of the first phase of the nation's first 24-hour commercial airport slated for 1993 <PERSON> Mitsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Omura </PERSON>, representing the eight-company <ORGANIZATION> Offshore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference in <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> Wednesday the cartel was `` necessary and an appropriate method to smoothly carry out a big national project'' like the Kansai airport. But an official at major construction firm <ORGANIZATION> Ohbayashi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said, `` We will discuss the matter with other firms a way to accept the commission's order.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> identified the members of the cartel as <ORGANIZATION> Ohbayashi </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kajima </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aoki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Takenaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doboku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Saeki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kensetsu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kogyo </PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION> Yorigami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The mass-circulation <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the six firms would be fined a total of $ 2.2 million in surcharges, equivalent to 1.5 percent of the total value of sand supplied to the project. The construction association, which has two weeks to notify the antitrust agency whether it will comply with the order, faces exclusion from bidding on public works projects, including those of other local governments, the newspaper said.
