<FIRST>u f AM-HyperCar Bjt   09-07 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hyper Car, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Companies Bet Big on Super Fast Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As American kids grow bored with video games and stop buying them, toy companies are hoping to pick up the slack by importing the latest craze from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>: 6-inch model cars that move at the equivalent, when scaled up to full size, of 320 miles per hour. But executives who gathered in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> for a toy industry conference Thursday expressed one nagging doubt about their new `` hyper cars.'' The darn things move so fast, how can kids possibly play with them? `` It's a real problem,'' conceded <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, vice president for finance at <ORGANIZATION> Matchbox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> `` You put it down on the rug and let it go, and it's just going to shoot off and keep going until it hits something or flips over.'' The $ 5 to $ 12 cars, powered by two or three AA batteries, move at actual speeds of about 10 miles per hour. But in comparison with their scale, which is 1-32 of a full-sized car, they easily outrun Formula I racers. Matchbox and its major competitors _ <ORGANIZATION> Hasbro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tonka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ plan to spend a total of $ 20 million to $ 25 million by Christmas to promote the flashy vehicles, most of which are just now hitting retail stores. It's an unusually late product introduction for the industry, and a marketing gamble driven by equal parts of excitement and worry. At the International Toy Fair in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in January, when new products traditionally are unveiled, <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tonka </ORGANIZATION> displayed their super-fast cars but were virtually ignored by retailers. Since then, however, two things have happened. One is that the cars have taken off in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, selling an estimated 45 million units and whetting the appetites of American toy store chains. The other is that the $ 2 billion-a-year market for video games may have peaked, and no `` hot'' new toys have emerged since <ORGANIZATION> Cabbage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dolls </ORGANIZATION> and the board game Trivial Pursuit racked up hundreds of millions of dollars in sales in the mid-1980s. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shank </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Tonka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive officer, told the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> toy conference that he expects `` an orderly decline'' in video game sales starting next year, and <ORGANIZATION> Tonka </ORGANIZATION> has decided to drop its Sega video line in 1990. The last time there was a downturn in video games, in 1980-81, several toy companies' profits plunged and `` it got pretty bloody out there,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, a toy industry analyst for the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the conference's sponsor. To avoid such a debacle again, toymakers have been casting about for something with enough sparkle to pull parents and children back into the toy stores. `` The industry has lacked a hot product for two years, and everyone thinks this -LRB- hyper car -RRB- thing could be it,'' said <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferretti </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Tons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toys </ORGANIZATION>, a chain of 25 stores in the Northeast. The cars come in numerous designs, inclding some with interchangeable motors and gear boxes. Although they are being marketed under various names, such as Hyper-Drivers and Record Breakers, most versions are made in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and are nearly identical in construction. Toymakers hope to solve the problem of how to play with the speeding vehicles by selling plastic track that kids can put together in their bedrooms, garages or backyards. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, arcades have installed elaborate tracks that junior racers pay to use. But some toy executives are doubtful the same thing will happen in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tyco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the leading maker of slot cars and radio-controlled vehicles, has decided to sit out the craze. `` We do n't think it's a good product, we do n't think it has good play value, and we do n't think it's going to be successful,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tyco </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grey </PERSON> told the industry conference. `` We're prepared to be wrong But we're also willing to stand up and be counted.''
</TEXT>
