<FIRST>r f AM-FarmReport 1stLd-Writethru f0106 09-07 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Report, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0106,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Report Urges Soil Conservation, Fewer Chemicals</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New information thruout. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government farm programs must encourage alternative methods of food production that save the soil and use fewer chemical fertilizers, weedkillers and pesticides, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> report said Thursday. Federal farm policies `` have generally made a plentiful food supply a higher priority than protection'' of the nation's soil and water resources, the report said. Instead of supporting `` environmentally benign'' ways of producing food, the report said, government programs have worked against those alternative methods. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON>, a coordinator for Americans for a Safe Food, a subsidiary of the private, non-profit Center for Science in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION>, said she agreed with the report's charge that government farm policies have been an impediment. `` Some of the basic agricultural policies that have been in motion almost since World War II have pushed the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> farmer into a high-chemical -LRB- method of -RRB- farming and makes it difficult, if not impossible, for the farmer to move into more sustainable practices,'' she said. <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON>'s group earlier this year released a study showing that efforts to promote organic and low-chemical farming `` is flourishing at the state level,'' while the federal effort is moving slowly. The latest report, `` Alternative Agriculture,'' came after a three-year $ 625,000 study by a 17-member committee headed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pesek </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The council is an agency of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and Engineering. As used in the 450-page report, alternative agriculture is not a single system of farm production with a siple list of do's and do n'ts It is a generic term that includes a wide range of methodology and labels _ organic, biological, low-input, regenerative, sustainable. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> uses its own acronym _ <LOCATION> LISA </LOCATION>, for low-input, sustainable agriculture _ in a bid to help farmers find lower-cost ways of producing crops and livestock while helping protect the environment. Assistant Secretary <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said at <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has already authorized a number of program changes to give more choices to farmers and that flexibility will be an important part of drafting a 1990 farm bill to replace the 1985 law. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> told reporters that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also has expanded its work in <ORGANIZATION> IPM </ORGANIZATION>, or integrated pest management, which uses a variety of methods to control crop pests instead of the old practice of dousing fields with pesticides. The report recommended that the department boost its spending on <ORGANIZATION> LISA </ORGANIZATION> to at least $ 40 million a year from the current level of $ 4.45 million. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said the total <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> research budget is about $ 1.2 billion this year and that a substantial upgrading of that is under review. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> acknowledged that there has been `` a major step forward in the last five years'' in the recognition of alternative farm methods. This has been a `` shared repsonsibility'' of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, the land-grant universities and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, he said. Only a few of the nation's 2.17 million farms have adopted entire alternative systems of production. But the report said the need is there and that bits and pieces have been successfully used. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said there is `` no magic formula, and the practices will vary from farm to farm.'' Crop rotations, in which soil-building crops are grown after the production of corn or other grain for several years, are examples of alternative methods. The conventional method might call for the same crop year after year, with farmers heaping on costly chemicals to boost production. `` Many federal policies discourage adoption of alternative practices and systems by economically penalizing those who adopt rotations, apply certain soil conservation systems, or attempt to reduce pesticide applications,'' the report said. `` Federal programs often tolerate and sometimes encourage unrealistically high yield goals, inefficient fertilizer and pesticide use, and unsustainable use of land and water,'' it said. `` Many farmers in these programs manage their farms to maximize present and future program benefits, sometimes at the expense of environmental quality.'' A primary goal of commodity program reform should be `` the removal of the existing disincentives'' that discourage alternative methods of production. `` This step would ensure that farmers who employ crop rotations and recommended resource conservation practices are not deprived of farm-income support,'' the report said. Thus, it added, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to revise existing programs to eliminate penalties for farmers adopting crop rotations, and to allow more flexibility in substituting or adjusting acreage allotments to accommodate rotations. The American Farmland Trust, a non-profit conservation group based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the report `` documents the compatibility of economic concerns and conservation measures'' on the nation's farms `` Today many farmers successfully implement safe, sustainable agricultural practices,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossi </PERSON>, AFT president. `` However, there is no widespread coordination of these efforts.'' The study was financed mainly by a $ 410,000 grant from the W.K. <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Other private contributors put up the balance, and the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> provided $ 80,000.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The committee's report, <ORGANIZATION> Alternative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, is available from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, 2101 Constitution Ave., <LOCATION> N.W. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20418, for $ 19.95 per paperback copy, prepaid, or $ 29.95 for hardcover.
