<FIRST>r f AM-CapitalGains     09-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Says He'll Fight Capital-Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said Thursday he will vigorously oppose a capital-gains tax cut, which he called a giveaway to the rich that would have to be financed by middle-income taxpayers. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said he favors preferential tax treatment for capital gains, but only as part of a fair, progressive tax structure that would include raising the maximum tax rate paid by wealthier Americans on all types of income. `` The present proposal is unfair, unwise and will increase the deficit,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, told reporters. `` It will require middle-class taxpayers to make up that tax break for the wealthy.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> cited estimates that on average, a capital-gains reduction would be worth $ 31,000 a year to a person with income over $ 200,000. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is expected to approve a capital-gains cut next week. Until passage of the 1986 tax overhaul, capital gains _ which are profits from the sale of stock and other investments _ were taxed at a lower rate than other income. But the capital-gains preference _ as well as such breaks as deductions for sales taxes and universal <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounts </ORGANIZATION> _ was taken away so that tax rates on all kinds of income could be cut significantly. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised during the campaign last year to restore the preference for capital gains, arguing such action would spur investment and saving. He has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to cut the maximum capital-gains rate, now 33 percent, to 15 percent. A compromise reduction, which has the president's support, was proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga. It would cut the top rate for 2 -LCB- years to 20 percent, then raise it permanently to 28 percent and ensure that profits caused solely by inflation would not be taxed. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>' plan has the backing of a bare majority of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, but the panel's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership has delayed a vote in an effort to win support for a third plan. Offered by Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., the new proposal would `` index'' the value of investments so that inflation-caused gain would not be taxed But it would go a big step further for assets held for five or more years, exempting from taxation as much as half the price for which such an investment is sold. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said that because of the budget deficit, this is not the time to consider any cut in capital-gains taxes. Asked if he is `` prepared to go to the mat'' in opposition to a cut, he stomped his foot and replied `` yes.'' He said that if a preference is voted for capital gains, that would increase pressure to restore other breaks that were taken away in the 1986 overhaul. Coincidentally, Sens. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., introduced a bill Thursday that would restore slightly modified but fully deductible IRAs for all workers A worker, regardless of income, could avoid tax on up to $ 2,000 per year contributed to an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>; one with an unemployed spouse could contribute another $ 1,000. The worker would be allowed a tax credit for 15 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> contribution. Thus, one who made the maximum $ 2,000 contribution could save $ 300 in taxes. The 1986 law retained fully deductible IRAs only for those not covered by a company pension regardless of income, and couples earning less than $ 35,000 and single workers earning less than $ 25,000.
</TEXT>
