<FIRST>u f AM-CatastrophicCare 1stLd-Writethru f0125 09-07 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0125,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Tax-Writers Ready to Amend Catastrophic Care Provisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with GOP senators at White House, inserting new 5th
graf, Meanwhile ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> tax-writers, yielding to loud complaints from many older Americans, indicated Thursday they would join their <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counterparts and go along with major changes in Medicare insurance covering the costs of a catastrophic illness. Several members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, however, rejected a revision approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to cut costs for the higher-income elderly but raise them for older people with lower incomes. `` I want to make it clear at the outset that, as chairman, I will oppose any increase in the flat premium paid by retirees of modest means,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` We should neither repeal ... -LRB- catastrophic coverage -RRB- nor shift a greater share of costs ... to beneficiaries who can least afford them,'' said Sen. Spark <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, Republican congressional leaders met with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House. Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, told reporters afterward that several of the lawmakers told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the catastrophic care act `` ought to be repealed in toto.'' The program, enacted barely a year ago, is under heavy fire from some older Americans who say they do n't need the protection and from others _ mainly those with higher incomes _ who object that the coverage is financed only by the elderly and not by all taxpayers. About two-thirds of the cost of the catastrophic care insurance program is paid by the 41 percent of older citizens whose incomes are high enough that they owe federal income tax of more than $ 150. They pay a surtax of 15 percent on income tax above $ 150; about 1.8 million of the 33 million Medicare beneficiaries will pay the maximum surtax of $ 800 this year. The surtax rate is due to increase to 28 percent and the maximum surtax to $ 1,050 by 1993. The rest of the cost is financed through a flat fee of $ 4 per month per retiree. That fee is due to rise to $ 10.20 by 1993. Complaints from the elderly prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to reduce some catastrophic care benefits, cut the surtax rate by half and raise the flat monthly fee significantly. Those changes have not been enough to mollify the protesters, as Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., the Ways and Means chairman, learned; he was chased down a street in his hometown of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> by angry retirees last month `` You almost have a sense when you go home of being unwanted, unloved and unappreciated on this issue,'' Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., told colleagues Thursday The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is likely to begin voting on how to change the program Friday. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said it would prefer no change at all, but <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Diefenderfer </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, conceded `` that does n't seem to be what's going to happen. <PERSON> Diefenderfer </PERSON> noted that repeal of catastrophic care coverage would worsen the federal deficit in 1990 by as much as $ 7 billion because taxes earmarked for the program come in faster than benefits are paid out. Killing the program would automatically trigger across-the-board cuts in most federal spending. There is considerable support in the House for outright repeal of catastrophic care insurance, an idea that drew the support of Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo. `` I question the kind of commitment we made last year,'' he said, noting the program leans toward long-term hospital care. `` This is n't something they -LRB- older Americans -RRB- want,'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said. `` It's something they fear ..., being hooked up'' to life-support equipment and the like. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> staff outlined seven options for changing catastrophic care coverage, most of which would require retirees to pay a larger share of expenses but also allow them to reject the insurance _ but only if they also drop Medicare Part B, which covers physicians' fees. The panel has two basic proposals for changing the way the program is financed: _ Freeze the surtax rate at 10 or 15 percent and reduce the maximum annual surtax to $ 585 This would require retirees to continue paying most of the costs of coverage. _ Require non-retirees to pay a share of the cost of catastrophic insurance by raising to $ 60,000 the $ 48,000 maximum amount of wages subject to the 1.45 percent Medicare hospitalization tax The tax, paid as part of the Social Security tax through payroll deductions, is matched by the employer.
</TEXT>
