<HEAD>Oil Markets Maintain Upward Momentum But Rally Loses Some Energy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures finished with small to moderate gains Thursday as the recent rally in the energy markets appeared to weaken. Wholesale gasoline prices, which spurted Wednesday on reports of refinery fires, maintained much of their upward momentum, helped by a bullish weekly report on stocks. But prices of crude oil and wholesale home heating oil ran into resistance. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for October delivery of unleaded gasoline rose 0.52 cent to 55.63 cents a gallon, adding to Wednesday's gain of 1.35 cents. The November, December and January contracts also moved up. Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the October contract of No. 2 heating oil edged 0.02 cent higher to 55.50 cents a gallon, stabilizing after Wednesday's jump of 0.91 cent Contracts for more distant months ended with minor gains. The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled at $ 19.41 per 42-gallon barrel, up 13 cents from Wednesday when the contract settled with an increase of 23 cents. Other delivery months closed with small losses and gains. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, a vice president of energy futures trading at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said activity in the energy pits retained a positive tone even though some futures faltered. `` The market seemed to stall in crude but continued strong for gasoline,'' said <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>. `` On the day, we saw a very good consolidation period.'' Prices for gasoline recently have benefited from concerns about possible tightening in supplies temporarily. On Wednesday, a fire at <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> refinery and one at <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s refinery in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> added to the speculation. After the close of business Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> issued its weekly inventory statistics that were viewed as bullish for gasoline. The API reported a 5.8 million-barrel drawdown in gasoline stocks and a 1.5 million-barrel drawdown in crude stocks. The drop in gasoline inventories was larger than the market had expected while the crude figure was in line with projections.
