<FIRST>r f AM-CattleDisease     09-07 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle Disease,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experimental Vaccine for Cow Venereal Disease Shows Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental vaccine for a venereal disease that kills unborn calves appears to be controlling the illness that causes an estimated $ 500 million in losses annually nationwide, a researcher said Thursday. `` Within the next two or three months we'll begin to get a much better idea of just how efficient this product is,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Extension Veterinarian. `` But at this point, everything points toward the fact that this is going to be an extremely good vaccine for use in the field. `` We see it as a major breakthrough to controlling this disease.'' The vaccine for the sexually transmitted trichomoniasis is now available in 41 states under conditional license from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. Researchers estimate the vaccine reduces the incidence of trichomoniasis by more than 90 percent. <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, a microbiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON>, department chair at <ORGANIZATION> UNR </ORGANIZATION>'s Veterinary Medicine Department, began developing the vaccine a few years ago `` <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s cattlemen asked us to develop something because so many cattle were infected with this disease,'' said <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON>, citing statistics that 44.1 percent of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> cattle tested positive for the disease in 1987. Adult cows do n't show symptoms of the disease when infected with trichomoniasis that's spread during breeding. But cows with the illness can become infertile, abort or their fetuses die, <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON> said. Vaccinated cows tested so far in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> are `` clearing'' the trichomoniasis disease within weeks and there appears to be no embryonic damages, <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON> said. `` It's really amazing,'' he said. `` But we're still measuring the impact on whether we can save the embryos.'' Researchers are scheduled next week to check on a couple of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> cattle herds that have been vaccinated to determine whether the disease has killed any unborn calves. `` A key test will come in October when we test the cattle after 120 days of pregnancy,'' he said. `` But we're pretty optimistic because the disease appears to have the biggest effect in the 30 to 60 day period of pregnancy.'' Cows have a 282-day gestation period. An acutely infected herd can lose up to 40 percent of its calves while one that has been carrying the disease for years can lose as many as 10 percent of its unborn calves, <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON> said. If the vaccine is proven safe, <PERSON> Kvasnicka </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> is planning by Jan. 1 to decide whether to fully license the product that was refined by <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>. In the early 1980s, researchers in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> studied the disease, developing a vaccine for bulls. But <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said that did n't stop the disease. `` The problem with that approach is that if one bull in a herd fails to develop immunity and becomes infected, he passes the disease to every heifer he breeds,'' he explained. `` That is not a good way to go. We need to protect the whole herd.''
</TEXT>
