<HEAD>Belly Futures Surge On Hopes For Polish Pork Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Futures prices for frozen pork bellies soared the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on speculation that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s belly surplus could disappear in a package of food aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. On other markets, soybean futures posted strong gains while energy futures and precious metals futures were mixed. Frozen pork belly futures settled 2 cents higher across the board with the contract for delivery in February at 46.82 cents a pound. The rally helped lift livestock futures contracts: live cattle settled .12 cent to .55 cent higher with October at 72.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .58 cent higher with October at 82.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower to .40 cent higher with October at 39.75 cents a pound. The February pork-belly contract has risen about 21 percent in value since Aug. 1, when February bellies traded as low as 38.70 cents a pound. Most of the gains have occurred in the past week on hopes that some of the near-record supplies of bellies languishing in deep freeze will be given to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> along with other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities. `` We probably will end up shipping bellies to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON>, a livestock-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> AgriVisor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` The question is how many and when.'' A pork belly is the part of a pig from which bacon is made. The Agriculture Department's last count showed 96.4 million pounds of pork bellies in cold storage as of Aug. 1, the largest supply for that date since the record year of 1971. Analysts say the resulting drop in bacon prices has led to greater consumption and a more rapid movement of bellies out of freezers, so that the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Sept. 22 cold-storage report is expected to show 55 million to 60 million pounds in cold storage as of Sept. 1. When talk of a Polish pork-belly shipment first surfaced last week, traders were speculating the amount would be about 30 million pounds. On Wednesday, a financial news service reported the Poles were seeking 50,000 metric tons, or more than 110 million pounds each of bellies and beef. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been cautious in their statements about a possible shipment. On Thursday, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldthwait </PERSON>, an assistant administrator with the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s foreign agriculture service, said it was premature to talk about quantities or even about what commodities may be included in an aid package. <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON> said the market may be overreacting, but he conceded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> belly surplus no longer looked so enormous. `` When I start looking at the numbers being batted around, all of a sudden you're saying that what was an overabundance is not necessarily so,'' he said. Soybean futures prices reached two-week highs on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, boosted by perceptions of increased foreign demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soy products and by a bullish harvest forecast from <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, Tenn.-based <ORGANIZATION> Sparks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Sparks pegged the 1989 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean crop at 1.85 billion bushels compared with the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s August estimate of 1.91 billion bushels The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> will revise its crop estimates on Tuesday. If <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> is right, soybean prices could be headed for an extended stay above $ 6 a bushel, said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, a grain market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Soybeans settled 4 \ cents to 9 \ cents higher with September at $ 5.96 -RCB- a bushel; wheat futures settled 1 cent lower to 1 \ cents higher with September at $ 3.97 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with September at $ 2.36 -LCB- a bushel; oats were \ cent to 2 cents higher with September at $ 1.36 On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 13 cents higher with October at $ 19.41 a barrel; heating oil was .11 cent lower to .04 cent higher with October at 55.50 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .10 cent to .54 cent higher with October at 55.63 cents a gallon. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold futures settled $ 1.40 lower across the board with October at $ 362.30 a troy ounce; silver was 1.3 cents to 1.7 cents higher with September at $ 5.117 a troy ounce.
