<HEAD>Seven New York Firms to Provide Emergency Child Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The seven ...,' to RESTORE name of seventh company.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, `A mixture ...'. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven large companies will offer at-home emergency child care to more than 13,000 employees in a yearlong experiment in day-care assistance. The employees will qualify for emergency assistance in a variety of situations that typically force parents to stay home from work: when a child becomes ill and can not go to school, when the family's regular child care arrangements fall through, or when a parent is suddenly called away on business An employee will be entitled to use the service up to three consecutive days. `` This is a perfect example of what I have in mind when I write about the concept of the family-friendly workplace,'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zigler </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> professor and a longtime advocate of a national child care policy, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in a story published Thursday. The seven companies, all in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, are Home Box Office, <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the accounting firm <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, the electric utility <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Skadden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arps </LOCATION>, Slate, <PERSON> Meagher </PERSON>, & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Flom </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s largest law firm A mixture of bottom-line profit considerations and concern for employees spurred companies to create the program, officials said. `` We no longer live in communities where there are extended families, or where we even know our neighbors, so parents have no backup systems,'' said <PERSON> Karol </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, manager of the Work and Family Program at Time. `` When an employee does n't come to work, or leaves a child in a situation he worries about, it is stressful for the employee and costly for the employer.'' Five participating companies will pay the full cost of the care, about $ 10.50 an hour, and the others will pay most of the cost, with employees covering the balance. Some companies expect the program to cut costs because of the high cost of temporary workers. For example, <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> pays $ 15 to $ 20 an hour to hire a temporary word processor, said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, a company spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
