<HEAD>EPA Orders Du Pont To Stop Sale Of Two Fungicides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chemical giant <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has been ordered to stop selling two fungicides which were contaminated with an herbicide during manufacture, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. The two fungicides, Benlate and <PERSON> Tersan </PERSON>, were contaminated with atrazine during manufacture by a subcontractor, <ORGANIZATION> Terra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blythe </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s office Use of the tainted fungicides poses potential risks of plant injury and illegal residue on food crops, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> reported. Benlate is registered for use on ornamental plants and certain food crops, while <PERSON> Tersan </PERSON> is registered for turf and ornamental uses. <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> said since atrazine is applied early in the growing season, residue from the pesticide is not normally found on crops. Because of that tolerance standards for atrazine residue have not been established by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. Benlate, however, is applied later in the growing season and because of that atrazine residue could show up, <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> said. However, the contamination does not pose a significant health threat, he said. The EPA issues between 1,000 and 2,000 stop-sale orders a year and the move is not considered unusual, <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Waltz </PERSON> said most of the product has already been sold and the company initiated a voluntary recall last month. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> issued the stop-sale order after receiving numerous complaints of plant injury nationwide, <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> said. Because atrazine is an herbicide, the contaminated Benlate was killing some of the plants it was applied on.
