 <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it had settled a dispute with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 325 million, less than a week before a trial was scheduled to begin in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. The dispute has been the subject of litigation between <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> and National Iranian since 1980 in courts in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as well as other proceedings, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> said. It involved National Iranian's claim for about $ 283 million of unpaid invoices for crude oil shipments to <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> in 1979, plus interest of about $ 285 million, for a total claim of about $ 768 million. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement the settlement was fair and in the best interests of both parties. `` Ashland never disputed receiving the crude oil or that it was obligated to pay a reasonable price for it,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said in the release. `` Ashland simply wished to recover losses it sustained in 1979 due to breaches of contract by <ORGANIZATION> NIOC </ORGANIZATION>. Considering Ashland had the use and benefit of $ 283 million for almost 10 years, we feel this settlement satisfactorily addresses our counterclaims.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> had counterclaimed in the courts for breaches of contract by National Iranian. A trial regarding National Iranian's claim was scheduled to start in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, on Sept. 11. No trial date had been set in a case in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said the settlement will result in a pre-tax charge of $ 42 million in <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s fiscal fourth quarter, ending Sept. 30. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's largest independent oil refiner.
