<HEAD>Appeals Court Sides With Chrysler Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals panel Thursday upheld <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in an antitrust lawsuit filed by three companies that buy and resell replacement parts for Chrysler-produced vehicles. A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld a ruling by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMascio </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aargus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Truck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, alleging the automaker illegally conspired to restrain trade. The companies also alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> attempted to monopolize the resale of Chrysler-produced auto parts to Chrysler-franchised dealers and to the government. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> argued that it and about 2,400 independent manufacturers or suppliers of compatible replacement parts compete for the replacement parts market. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also argued that the plaintiffs failed to prove their monopoly allegations because <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the replacement-parts market was only about 20 percent. DeMascio, presiding at a trial of the lawsuit, issued rulings in February and May 1988 in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>. The three plaintiff companies appealed. The companies buy and resell Chrysler-produced and compatible replacement parts for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> vehicles. Businessman <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Henke </PERSON> owns and operates the three companies through stock ownership.
